{"title_page": "Mitelman Database of Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer", "text_new": "{{short description|Medical database}}\nThe '''Mitelman Database of Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer''' is a free access database devoted to chromosomes, genes, and cancer. It was first published in 1983 as a book named \"Catalog of Chromosome aberrations in Cancer\" in the Journal of Cytogenetics and Cell Genetics, containing 3,844 cases<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of Chromosome Aberrations in Cancer |journal=Cytogenetic and Genome Research |date=1983 |volume=36 |issue=1-2 |pages=1\u20133 |doi=10.1159/000131930}}</ref>. Subsequent editions of the Catalog were published 1985 (5,345 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1985 |publisher=Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-8451-2405-6 |page=707 |edition=2nd}}</ref>, 1988 (9,069 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1988 |publisher=Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-8451-4248-8 |page=1146 |edition=3rd}}</ref> , 1991 (14,141 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1991 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-56087-1 |page=1986 |edition=4th}}</ref> , 1994\n(22,076 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=MItelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1994 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-11183-X |page=4252 |edition=5th}}</ref> , and 1998 (30,541 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer '98 |date=1998 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-17603-6 |edition=6th}}</ref>. In 2000, it became an online database on open access hosted by the [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]] (National Cancer Institute).\n\nThe information in the Mitelman Database of Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer relates [[cytogenetic]] changes and their genomic consequences, in particular [[Fusion gene|gene fusions]], to [[Neoplasm|tumor]] characteristics, based either on individual cases or associations. All the data have been manually culled from the literature by [[Felix Mitelman]] in collaboration with Bertil Johansson and Fredrik Mertens.\n\n\"Taking in consideration all the progress made in cancer cytogenetics, it would have been much slower without the Mitelman database.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Cancer Cytogenomics Resources |url=http://atlasgeneticsoncology.org/Deep/Cancer_CytogenomicsID20145.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Mitelman Database is supported by [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]] (National Cancer Institute), the Swedish Cancer Society and the Swedish Childhood Cancer Foundation. The database is updated quarterly in January, April, July, and October.\n\nThe database is available on-line (https://mitelmandatabase.isb-cgc.org) for searches related to  cases [[cytogenetics]], [[Fusion gene|gene fusions]], clinical associations, structural or numerical recurrent aberrations and references.\n\nThe database was last updated on Apr 15th, 2020, with a total number of cases=70,236, a total number of unique gene fusions=31,626 and a total number of genes involved=13,913<ref>{{cite web |title=Mitelman Database: About |url=https://mitelmandatabase.isb-cgc.org/about |website=Mitelman Database: Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer |accessdate=16 Jan 2020}}</ref>.\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Atlas of Genetics and Cytogenetics in Oncology and Haematology]] \n* [[COSMIC cancer database]]\n* [[Ensembl genome database project]]\n* [[Entrez Gene]]\n* [[GenBank]]\n* [[Gene Wiki]]\n* [[HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee]]\n* [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]]\n* [[International Classification of Diseases for Oncology]]\n* [[Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man]] \n* [[UCSC Genome Browser]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cancer]]\n[[Category:Oncology]]\n[[Category:Cytogenetics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Medical database}}\nThe '''Mitelman Database of Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer''' is a free access database devoted to chromosomes, genes, and cancer. It was first published in 1983 as a book named \"Catalog of Chromosome aberrations in Cancer\" in the Journal of Cytogenetics and Cell Genetics, containing 3,844 cases<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of Chromosome Aberrations in Cancer |journal=Cytogenetic and Genome Research |date=1983 |volume=36 |issue=1-2 |pages=1\u20133 |doi=10.1159/000131930}}</ref>. Subsequent editions of the Catalog were published 1985 (5,345 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1985 |publisher=Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-8451-2405-6 |page=707 |edition=2nd}}</ref>, 1988 (9,069 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1988 |publisher=Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-8451-4248-8 |page=1146 |edition=3rd}}</ref> , 1991 (14,141 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1991 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-56087-1 |page=1986 |edition=4th}}</ref> , 1994\n(22,076 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=MItelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer |date=1994 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-11183-X |page=4252 |edition=5th}}</ref> , and 1998 (30,541 cases)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitelman |first1=Felix |title=Catalog of chromosome aberrations in cancer '98 |date=1998 |publisher=Wiley-Liss |location=New York |isbn=0-471-17603-6 |edition=6th}}</ref>. In 2000, it became an online database on open access hosted by the [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]] (National Cancer Institute).\n\nThe information in the Mitelman Database of Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer relates [[cytogenetic]] changes and their genomic consequences, in particular [[Fusion gene|gene fusions]], to [[Neoplasm|tumor]] characteristics, based either on individual cases or associations. All the data have been manually culled from the literature by [[Felix Mitelman]] in collaboration with Bertil Johansson and Fredrik Mertens.\n\n\"Taking in consideration all the progress made in cancer cytogenetics, it would have been much slower without the Mitelman database.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Cancer Cytogenomics Resources |url=http://atlasgeneticsoncology.org/Deep/Cancer_CytogenomicsID20145.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Mitelman Database is supported by [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]] (National Cancer Institute), the Swedish Cancer Society and the Swedish Childhood Cancer Foundation. The database is updated quarterly in January, April, July, and October.\n\nThe database is available on-line (https://mitelmandatabase.isb-cgc.org) for searches related to  cases [[cytogenetics]], [[Fusion gene|gene fusions]], clinical associations, structural or numerical recurrent aberrations and references.\n\nThe database was last updated on Jan 15th, 2020, with a total number of cases=69,956, a total number of unique gene fusions=32,769 and a total number of genes involved=14,579<ref>{{cite web |title=Mitelman Database: About |url=https://mitelmandatabase.isb-cgc.org/about |website=Mitelman Database: Chromosome Aberrations and Gene Fusions in Cancer |accessdate=16 Jan 2020}}</ref>.\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Atlas of Genetics and Cytogenetics in Oncology and Haematology]] \n* [[COSMIC cancer database]]\n* [[Ensembl genome database project]]\n* [[Entrez Gene]]\n* [[GenBank]]\n* [[Gene Wiki]]\n* [[HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee]]\n* [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]]\n* [[International Classification of Diseases for Oncology]]\n* [[Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man]] \n* [[UCSC Genome Browser]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cancer]]\n[[Category:Oncology]]\n[[Category:Cytogenetics]]\n", "name_user": "Eleeisb", "label": "safe", "comment": "Data release info update as of Apr, 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitelman_Database_of_Chromosome_Aberrations_and_Gene_Fusions_in_Cancer"}
{"title_page": "AfriForum", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox organisation\n| name = AfriForum\n| native_name = \n| former_name = \n| image = AfriForum_logo.svg\n| image_border = \n| size = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption = \n| map = \n| msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption = \n| map2 = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = Laat jou stem hoor (English: Let your voice be heard)\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| formation = 26 March 2006<!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| founder = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| extinction = <!-- {{End date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger = \n| merged = \n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| professional_title = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters = Union Street, [[Kloofsig]], [[Centurion, Gauteng|Centurion]], [[Gauteng]]\n| location = \n| coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using {{Coord}} -->\n| region_served = \n| services = \n| membership = 235,000 (March 2020)<ref name=\"Politicsweb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/politics/meeting-with-health-minister-requested-regarding-n|title=AfriForum requests meeting with Health Minister regarding NHI|work=[[Politicsweb]]|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|author=Bester, Carina}}</ref>\n| leader_name = Kallie Kriel\n| leader_title2 = Deputy CEO\n| leader_name2 = [[Ernst Roets]]\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3 = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4 = \n| board_of_directors = \n| key_people = \n| main_organ = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = <!-- or | parent_organisation = , if one -->\n| subsidiaries = \n| affiliations = Solidarity Movement\n| budget = \n| num_staff = \n| num_volunteers = \n| slogan = \n| website = {{url|afriforum.co.za}}\n| remarks = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''AfriForum''' is a [[South Africa]]n non-governmental organisation focused on the interests of [[Afrikaners]], a subgroup of the country's [[white South Africans|white]] population. AfriForum has been described as a [[Lobbying|lobby group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news/item/470-human-rights-commission-receives-complaints-against-up-afriforum|title=Human Rights Commission receives complaints against UP, Afriforum|website=www.sahrc.org.za}}</ref>, and AfriForum refers to itself as a [[Civil_and_political_rights|civil rights group]], but it has also been referred to as an Afrikaner nationalist group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1035262/self-declared-traitors-of-the-volk-trash-afriforum/|title=\u2018Traitors of the volk\u2019 trash AfriForum|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>, a white rights group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/trump-south-africa-714744/|title=Trump Is Using a White Nationalist Conspiracy Theory to Inform Policy|first1=Ryan|last1=Bort|first2=Ryan|last2=Bort|date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> and a [[White_nationalism|white nationalist group]],<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/south-africa-white-farmers-plaasmoorde-can il-ramaphosa-anc-economic-freedom-fighters-gabriel-stols-a8262306.html</ref> a description rejected by the organisation's leadership.<ref name=\u201cvoa\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/white-nationalism-moves-south-african-mainstream-politics|title=White Nationalism Moves Into South African Mainstream Politics|website=[[Voice of America]]}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 2006 to encourage the re-engagement of Afrikaners in the public sphere,<ref name=visser>{{cite web|last=Visser |first=Wessel P |title=From MWU To Solidarity \u2013 A Trade Union Reinventing Itself |url=http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departemente1/geskiedenis/docs/from_mwu_to_solidarity.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=University Of Stellenbosch |accessdate=14 January 2014 |page=20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811050629/http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departemente1/geskiedenis/docs/from_mwu_to_solidarity.pdf |archivedate=11 August 2013 }}</ref> it is closely affiliated to the [[Solidarity_(South_African_trade_union)|Solidarity]] [[trade union]],<ref name=\"huffPoParallelState\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/01/31/afriforum-and-solidaritys-parallel-state_a_21704173/|title=AfriForum And Solidarity's 'Parallel State'|date=31 January 2017|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref> and has attracted significant controversy because of a statement that [[Apartheid]] was not a [[Crimes against humanity|crime against humanity]].<ref name=\"timesLiveUproarApartheid\"/><ref name=\"bdlive-vanonselen-13032019\"/><ref name=\"news24-apartheid-irr-13032019\"/>  A court however ruled that \u201cKriel did not justify Apartheid or align himself with the racial discriminatory policies of the past. He stated unequivocally that Apartheid was wrong and that it was a system that infringed on the dignity of people\u201d. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/447418684/Black-First-Land-First-v-AfriForum-Kallie-Kriel-EQ-6-2018-Judgment-29-Oct-2019|title=Black First Land First v AfriForum & Kallie Kriel (EQ 6/2018) Judgment (29 Oct 2019)|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/10/29/afriforum-s-kriel-court-win-against-blf-proves-i-m-not-a-supporter-of-apartheid|title=AfriForum's Kriel: Court win against BLF proves I'm not a supporter of apartheid|last=Dlulane|first=Bonga|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  \n\nAfriForum is sometimes accused of advancing the idea of a [[White_genocide_conspiracy_theory|white genocide]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45336840|title=The groups playing on the fears of a 'white genocide\u2019|last=Chothia|first=Farouk|date=2018-09-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> with the organisation denying this, and lodging multiple successful complaints against media reporting that claimed it promotes the idea of a white genocide.<ref>{{cite web |title=[UPDATE] 'We have never ever said there is a white genocide happening in SA' |url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/316863/we-have-never-ever-said-there-is-a-white-genocide-happening-in-sa |website=702 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |language=en |date=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-mail--guardian-4366|title=AfriForum vs. Mail & Guardian|publisher=Press Council|access-date=2019-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302005952/https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-mail--guardian-4366|archive-date=2019-03-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAfriForum was founded in 2006 following public consultations about its charter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180326/http://www.afriforum.co.za/mediaverklarings.htm|title=AfriForum : Media|date=September 28, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180249/http://www.afriforum.co.za/dokumente.htm|title=AfriForum : Media|date=September 28, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>  In the preface to the charter, AfriForum refers to itself as a \u201ccitizen's right initiative founded by the trade union Solidarity\u201d.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180945/http://www.afriforum.co.za/dokumente/09 2006 voorwoord - burgerregte-manifes.doc</ref>\n\nBy March 2020 AfriForum had 235 000 contributing members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/politics/meeting-with-health-minister-requested-regarding-n|title=AfriForum requests meeting with Health Minister regarding NHI - POLITICS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIts leader, Kallie Kriel, was previously a member of the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]], and a leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) youth wing, and a large number of its executive leadership were formerly associated with Freedom Front Plus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thoughtleader.co.za/thornegodinho/2014/01/08/afriforum-and-the-rise-of-the-new-right/|title=AfriForum and the rise of the new right &#124; Thought Leader}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns, policies and projects==\n[[File:AfriForum - Standerton-betoging.jpg|thumb|left|AfriForum protest outside the [[Pretoria High Court]]]]\n\n===Crime and corruption===\n====Farm attacks====\nAfriForum has been a vocal critic of the [[ANC]]'s response to [[South African farm attacks]], claiming that the party bears a responsibility for \"remain[ing] silent\" about the violence,<ref name=blamfm>{{cite web|title=AfriForum blames ANC for farm murders|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2012/09/12/afriforum-blames-anc-for-farm-murders|publisher=Times LIVE|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> and lodging a complaint to the [[South African Human Rights Commission]] against the [[Department of Police (South Africa)|Police Minister]] for failing to do enough to protect farmers.<ref name=farmiol>{{cite web|title=Afriforum takes farm murders to SAHRC|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/afriforum-takes-farm-murders-to-sahrc-1.1524798|publisher=IOL.co.za|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> The organisation launched the book ''Kill the Boer''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.killtheboerbook.com/reviews/|title=Reviews - Kill the Boer Book|work=Kill the Boer Book|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> written by [[Ernst Roets]], the organisation's deputy CEO.<ref name=\"Hlatshaneni\">{{cite news |last1=Hlatshaneni |first1=Simnikiwe |title=Outrage surrounds book claiming top ANC officials \u2018killed the boer\u2019 |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1964479/outrage-surrounds-book-claiming-top-anc-officials-killed-the-boer/ |accessdate=24 November 2018 |newspaper=[[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]] |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation also launched the Wilmien Potgieter Fund to assist children who were victims of farm attacks often resulting in the loss of one or both parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/en/farm-attacks-increase-farm-murders-decrease/|title=Farm attacks increase, but farm murders decrease|last=AfriForum|date=2019-01-29|website=AfriForum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n====Private prosecutions====\nThe organisation formed a [[private prosecution]]s unit, headed by well-known former state prosecutor [[Gerrie Nel]], amid allegations that the [[National Prosecuting Authority]] (NPA) was selective in prosecutions, and politically biased.<ref name=\"conversationHowPrivateProsecutionsWillWork\">{{Cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/explainer-how-south-africas-first-private-prosecutions-unit-will-work-72389|title=Explainer: how South Africa's first private prosecutions unit will work|last=Feldhaus|first=Chantelle|work=[[The Conversation]]|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> \n\n[[Grace Mugabe]], the wife of [[Robert Mugabe]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/gerrie-nel-takes-on-grace-mugabe-will-assist-alleged-assault-victim/ | title=Gerrie Nel takes on Grace Mugabe, announces plan to assist alleged assault victim| date=2017-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nehandaradio.com/2017/08/17/gerrie-nel-sets-sights-grace-mugabe/|title=Gerrie Nel sets sights on Grace Mugabe \u2013 Nehanda Radio|date=2017-08-17|work=Nehanda Radio|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/as-gerrie-nel-targets-grace-mugabe-we-remember-the-bulldogs-biggest-cases/ | title=As Gerrie Nel targets Grace Mugabe, we remember the bulldog's biggest cases| date=2017-08-18}}</ref> and [[Duduzane Zuma]], son of then-President [[Jacob Zuma]], were targeted by the unit for prosecution after the NPA showed reluctance to prosecute them for assault, and [[culpable homicide]], respectively.<ref name=\"ewnBLfConfrontKriel\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/12/blf-confront-afriforum-s-kriel-after-duduzane-zuma-court-appearance | title=BLF confront AfriForum's Kriel after Duduzane Zuma court appearance}}</ref> Following AfriForum's move to privately prosecute Zuma, the National Prosecuting Authority decided to pursue a prosecution instead.<ref name=\"ewnStrongCaseZuma\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/12/gerrie-nel-afriforum-has-strong-case-against-duduzane-zuma | title=Gerrie Nel: AfriForum has strong case against Duduzane Zuma}}</ref> The organisation also undertook a prosecution of the chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]], [[Thandi Modise]], after allegations of [[animal cruelty]] at her [[North West (South Africa)|North West]] farm.<ref name=\"encaScoresModise\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.enca.com/scores-dead-animals-found-thandi-modises-farm | title=Scores of dead animals found on Thandi Modise's farm}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ToProsecuteModise\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-to-privately-prosecute-thandi-modise-20180719 | title=AfriForum to privately prosecute Thandi Modise over animal cruelty| date=2018-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"ewnTakeOnCruelty\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/19/afriforum-to-take-on-thandi-modise-for-animal-cruelty | title=AfriForum to privately prosecute Thandi Modise for animal cruelty}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, AfriForum undertook a private prosecution of EFF leader [[Julius Malema]] on charges of fraud and corruption, after the NPA failed to continue prosecuting the case.<ref name=\"iolMalemaAfriForumExplainsCase\"/> AfriForum had initially laid the charges against Malema in 2011.<ref name=\"iolMalemaAfriForumExplainsCase\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/why-prosecute-malema-afriforum-explains-its-case-14536130|title=Why prosecute Malema? AfriForum explains its case - IOL News|publisher=}}</ref> It also exerted pressure on authorities to investigate and prosecute Malema for discharging a firearm at a rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/malema-receiving-preferential-treatment-npa-claims-lobby-group/|title=Malema receiving preferential treatment from NPA, claims lobby group|website=Jacaranda FM}}</ref>\n\n===Education, language and culture===\nAfriForum has strongly opposed the proposed renaming of South Africa's capital from [[Pretoria]] to Tshwane, as well as street renaming in Pretoria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/81-against-Pretoria-name-change-20130414|title=81% against Pretoria name change|work=News24|date=2013-04-14}}</ref> \n\nThe organisation campaigns to promote mother tongue education<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/01/17/afrikaans-schools-have-a-right-to-be-here-afriforum_a_23335475/|title='Afrikaans Schools Have A Right To Be Here' -- AfriForum|date=2018-01-17|work=HuffPost South Africa|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-ZA}}</ref> and keep religion in schools.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2017-06-28-mixed-reaction-to-courts-ruling-against-single-religion-schools/|title=Mixed reaction to court\u2019s ruling against single-religion schools|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-afriforum-ready-for-legal-battle-to-keep-religion-in-schools-2016-02-24|title=AfriForum: AfriForum ready for legal battle to keep religion in schools|website=Polity.org.za}}</ref> and has clashed with Gauteng MEC for Basic Education [[Panyaza Lesufi]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/youre-defending-your-territory-not-a-language-lesufi-tells-afriforum-20160602|title=You\u2019re defending your territory, not a language, Lesufi tells AfriForum|work=CityPress|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref> who the organisation perceives as being hostile to [[Afrikaans in schools]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/en/afriforum-welcomes-panyaza-lesufis-move-education/|title=AfriForum welcomes Panyaza Lesufi\u2019s move from education|date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> because of proposed school regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/let-me-be-clear-i-will-make-no-apology-lesufi-responds-to-ff-plus-on-afrikaans-schools-20181026|title='Let me be clear, I will make no apology' - Lesufi responds to FF Plus on Afrikaans schools|date=October 26, 2018|website=News24}}</ref> {{clarify|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn 2008, Afriforum laid a charge of attempting to defeat the ends of justice against a senior superintendent of the SAPS forensics laboratory in Pretoria who refused to receive evidence in over 50 cases (including murder and rape) because the covering letter was in Afrikaans.<ref name=tra>{{cite web|last1=Trapido |first1=Michael |title=No country for Afrikaans then? |url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/traps/2008/07/16/petty-apartheid-revisited/|website=[[Thought Leader]] |publisher=Mail&Guardian |date = July 16, 2008 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Land===\n{{see|Land reform in South Africa}}\nAfriForum is involved in issues regarding [[land reform in South Africa|land reform]], blaming the \"corruption\" and \"incompetence\" of the [[Department of Rural Development and Land Reform]] for the slow pace of land reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821115109/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2012/06/27/afriforum-slams-zuma-land-comments|title=AfriForum slams Zuma land comments |publisher= Times LIVE|date=August 21, 2014|via=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum has assisted black landowners who were victims of [[squatting|squatters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/mobi/Detail.aspx?NewsID=47994&CatID=1009 |title=Eviction order for land invaders given go-ahead |work=thenewage.co.za |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821041728/http://www.thenewage.co.za/mobi/Detail.aspx?NewsID=47994&CatID=1009 |archivedate=2014-08-21 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/southafrica/news/pretoria-land-invasion-case-continues-20120202|title=Pretoria land invasion case continues|date=February 2, 2012|website=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/southafrica/news/pretoria-land-invaders-ordered-to-move-20120202|title=Pretoria land invaders ordered to move|date=February 2, 2012|website=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/party/bank-accounts-of-wallmansthal-land-grabber-frozen-|title=Bank accounts of Wallmansthal land grabber frozen - AfriForum - PARTY &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.za/department-hand-over-title-deeds-wallmansthal-and-berlin-mission-claimants|title=Department to hand over title deeds to Wallmansthal and Berlin mission claimants &#124; South African Government|website=www.gov.za}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation appeared before a parliamentary committee to oppose proposed constitutional amendments to allow for expropriation without compensation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/you-are-drunk-on-the-ideology-of-the-ndr--ernst-ro|title=You are drunk on the ideology of the NDR - Ernst Roets - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2018-09-06-afriforum-bemoans-fallacy-that-whites-stole-the-land/|title=AfriForum bemoans \u2018fallacy that whites stole the land\u2019|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> and, in August 2018, AfriForum controversially published a list of farms that are said to be targeted by the government for expropriation without compensation that the organisation received from an anonymous source.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/this-is-the-list-of-farms-targeted-for-ewc--afrifo|title=This is the list of farms targeted for EWC - AfriForum - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> Although the organisation received a backlash from some organisations and political parties regarding the legitimacy of the list, the South African Institute for Race Relations confirmed and corroborated the legitimacy of the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/land-expropriation-list-released-by-afriforum-is-legitimate-irr-20180814|title='Land expropriation list released by AfriForum is legitimate' \u2013 IRR|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum successfully complained about a column published on [[News24]] by journalist [[Pieter du Toit]] regarding its testimony before the parliamentary committee discussing amending the constitution to allow for expropriation without compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115215150/http://www.presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-news24-4356|title=AfriForum vs. News24|publisher=Press Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Apology to AfriForum for 'no solutions' claim in land column |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-afriforum-for-no-solutions-claim-in-land-column-20181116 |website=News24 |language=en |date=16 November 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Racism and hate speech campaigns===\nIn April 2011, AfriForum opened a civil case against [[Julius Malema]], in the [[Equality Court]] after he sang the words \u201cdubul\u2019 ibhunu\u201d, which translates as \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|shoot the boer]]\u201d, at ANC Youth League gatherings.<ref>Benesch, Susan (2012). \"Words as Weapons\". World Policy Journal. 29 (1): 7\u201312. doi:10.1177/0740277512443794. JSTOR 41510486.</ref><ref name=shtbs>{{cite news|title=ANC youth leader denies hatred in 'Shoot the boer' song|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/20/julius-malema-hate-speech-boer|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=2011-04-20|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> It was ruled that the song constituted [[hate speech]] and undermined the dignity of Afrikaners, and was discriminatory and harmful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2011-09-12-shoot-the-boer-its-hate-speech-says-judge|title='Shoot the boer': It's hate speech, says judge|author=Staff Reporter, Sapa-AFP|work=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref name=stbban>{{cite news|title=ANC Julius Malema's Shoot the Boer ruled 'hate speech'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14878102|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=2011-09-12}}</ref> In 2012, AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]] (SCA) in [[Bloemfontein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Shoot-the-Boer-appeal-canned-20121031-2|title=Shoot the Boer appeal canned|work=News24|date=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum has laid criminal charges against other political figures,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/hate-speech-charge-laid-against-lamola-20120709-2/ |title=Hate speech charge laid against Lamola |work=News24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211202232/http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/hate-speech-charge-laid-against-lamola-20120709-2/ |archivedate=2012-12-11 }}</ref> and social media users that it deemed to be inciting violence and racism,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1510149/afriforum-lay-hate-charges-facebooker/|title=AfriForum lays hate speech charges against \u2018kill pink pigs\u2019 Facebooker|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> In June the same year, AfriForum said that they plan to lay criminal charges against 100 social media users for incitement of violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1554475/afriforum-to-lay-charges-against-these-100-social-media-users/|title=AfriForum to lay charges against these 100 social media users|last=reporter|first=Citizen|work=The Citizen|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-lays-criminal-charges-against-police-officials-2018-06-18|title=AfriForum lays criminal charges against police officials|work=Polity.org.za|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/sandf-member-caught-in-alleged-race-row-with-civilian-18801565|title=SANDF member caught in alleged race row with civilian &#124; Cape Times|website=www.iol.co.za}}</ref> and created a unit against racism and hate speech.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-launches-anti-racism-unit-20170911|title=AfriForum launches anti-racism unit|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/afriforum-stig-teenrassisme-eenheid-2/|title=AfriForum stig teenrassisme-eenheid|date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> It also addressed racist incidents involving a number of people,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/south-africans-have-double-standards-when-it-comes-to-racism-afriforum-20170216|title=South Africans have double standards when it comes to racism|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2011/09/08/AfriForum-welcomes-Darren-Scotts-apology|title=AfriForum welcomes Darren Scott's apology|last=News|first=Eyewitness|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> Dan Roodt,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/AfriForum-condemns-racist-Dan-Roodt-20141113|title=AfriForum condemns 'racist' Dan Roodt|date=2014-11-13|access-date=2018-09-26|work=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-22-afriforum-condemns-use-of-k-word-by-catzavelos-urges-consistency-in-condemnation-of-racism-from-all-sides/|title=AfriForum condemns use of k-word by Catzavelos\u201a urges consistency in condemnation of racism from all sides|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> and the paramilitary [[Kommandokorps]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kommandokorps-denies-racism-20120227|title=Kommandokorps denies racism|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> and has stated that it regards the use of the 'k-word' [[Kaffir (racial term)|kaffir]] to be a \"gross human rights violation\".<ref name=sabckword>{{cite web|title=AfriForum reaffirm stance on use of K-word amid racist saga|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/aa9441804fe8018d8628e60b5d39e4bb/AfriForum-reaffirm-stance-on-use-of-K-word-amid-racist-saga|publisher=SABC News|accessdate=14 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116083121/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/aa9441804fe8018d8628e60b5d39e4bb/AfriForum-reaffirm-stance-on-use-of-K-word-amid-racist-saga|archive-date=16 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nAfriforum opposed restrictions imposed by the Equality Court in 2019 on the \"gratuitous display\" of the [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|old South African flag]], claiming that such restrictions limited freedom of speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/afriforum-says-apartheid-flag-ruling-is-setback-for-freedom-of-speech-31059834|title=AfriForum says apartheid flag ruling is setback for freedom of speech &#124; IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za}}</ref>\n\n===Minority rights===\nAfriForum has engaged with the [[United Nations]] on minority rights issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/Minority/Pages/Session8OralWrittenStatements.aspx|title=OHCHR &#124; Oral statements delivered at the Forum/Written Submissions during the 8th session|website=www.ohchr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.ohchr.org/results.aspx?k=afriforum|title=Search Center|website=search.ohchr.org}}</ref> and has criticised the ruling ANC about what it claims is a denial of minority rights in the country.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} However, ''[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]'' journalist [[Adriaan Basson]] has accused the organisation of overreacting to the situation regarding minority rights. Basson stated in an open letter to AfriForum CEO, Kallie Kriel, that the premise of AfriForum's campaigns is one of victimhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Columnists/GuestColumn/White-first-African-second-20110926|title=White first. African second|work=News24|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>  Subsequent to Basson's open letter, president [[Jacob Zuma]] told the national assembly that \"You have more rights because you're a majority; you have less rights because you're a minority. That's how democracy works\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/You-dont-understand-democracy-Zuma-told-20120914|title=You don't understand democracy, Zuma told|date=2012-09-14|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and [[African National Congress|ANC]] spokesperson Zizi Kodwa implied that being classified as a minority is a demotion when he stated that \"people who had played an integral part in the struggle should not feel as if they had been reduced to the status of a minority group\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/the-persecution-of-minority-communities-in-sa--afr|title=The persecution of minority communities in SA - AfriForum - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===International lobbying===\nAfriforum claimed credit for taking an [[Australia]]n journalist on a tour of South Africa, and for the \"dozens\" of articles detailing violent attacks on farms that subsequently appeared in the Australian media.<ref name=\"forumNuusUsaTour\">{{cite web|url=https://forumnuus.co.za/afriforum-se-kriel-en-roets-na-vsa-vir-bewusmaking-oor-plaasmoorde-en-onteiening/|title=AfriForum se Kriel en Roets na VSA vir bewusmaking oor plaasmoorde en onteiening|trans-title=Afriforum's Kriel and Roets travel to USA to raise awareness of farm murders and expropriation|quote= After an Australian journalist visiting South Africa was taken on a tour of South Africa by Afriforum, literally dozens of articles appeared in the Australian media about farm murders and the ANC government's misjudgment on property rights |publisher=Forum Nuus|date=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"huffPoDuToirPlayingWithFire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/pieter-du-toit/afriforums-u-s-adventure-playing-with-fire-after-setting-australia-alight_a_23426470/|title=AfriForum's U.S. Adventure: Playing With Fire, Just Like In Oz|date=4 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref><ref name=\"southAfricaAntiWhiteFrankChung\"/><ref name=\"smhDigIn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/africa/white-south-african-farmers-dig-in-against-deadly-persecution-20180317-p4z4vx.html|title=White South African farmers dig in against deadly 'persecution'|date=17 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inquirer/six-hours-of-torture-for-the-keys-to-an-empty-safe/news-story/2497280df1b18c31f55344d9f2dcf8f4|title=Killed because you're white|date=17 March 2018|newspaper=The Australian}}</ref><ref name=\"southAfricaAntiWhiteFrankChung\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/world-economy/south-africans-trapped-like-frogs-in-boiling-water-as-racial-violence-escalates/news-story/6882cebcd8d518cf949bb861b617d8ac|title=It is a very, very violent country|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"smhDigIn\"/>\n\nAfriForum also undertook a tour of the United States that included meetings with [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]], staffers for Senator [[Ted Cruz]], and an interview on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"ajLobbyingUnderFire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/south-african-group-fire-lobbying-white-rights-180514054424008.html|title=South African group under fire for lobbying US for white rights|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> AfriForum toured Australia in October 2018 to raise awareness of farm attacks. Ian Cameron from AfriForum was interviewed on [[Sky News Australia]]'s program [[Outsiders (Australian TV program)|Outsiders]] by [[Ross Cameron]] and Rowan Dean.<ref name=\"mailAndGuardian20181015\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-15-afriforum-decries-sa-farm-murders-down-under|title=AfriForum decries SA farm murders down under|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref> AfriForum also met Australian MP [[Andrew Hastie (politician)|Andrew Hastie]] and delivered a presentation before the [[Parliament of Western Australia]].<ref name=\"timesLive20181005\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-10-14-afriforum-in-australia-to-talk-about-farm-attacks-and-murders-in-sa/|title=AfriForum in Australia to talk about farm attacks and murders in SA|publisher=Times Live}}</ref>\n\n====Zimbabwe====\nThe group contested the presence of [[Robert Mugabe]] at the 2009 inauguration of [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref name=gsd>{{cite news|title=Great song and dance as Zuma is sworn in as president of South Africa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/may/07/south-africa-zuma-president-inauguration|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=14 January 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2009-05-07|last1=Correspondent|first1=David Smith Africa}}</ref> It was also involved in a bid to prevent the delivery of [[Alouette III]] Air Force helicopters to the [[Zimbabwe Army|Zimbabwean army]].<ref name=zimheli>{{cite news|title=AfriForum wins bid to halt Zim helicopter delivery|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-01-26-afriforum-wins-bid-to-halt-zim-helicopter-delivery|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 a legal team for AfriForum representing farmers in [[Zimbabwe]] won a court bid to sue Zimbabwe's government over its \u201ccruel\u201d and \u201cvengeful\u201d [[expropriation]] of South African-owned farms. In 2008 the regional court SADC tribunal ruled that [[Zimbabwe's land reform]] was illegal and racist, and that those who had suffered discrimination by having their farms expropriated had the right to compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/afriforum-wins-first-round-in-zimbabwe-case-1.470355|title=Afriforum wins first round in Zimbabwe case|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nAfriForum encourages communities to become self-sufficient. Activities undertaken have included a pothole fixing campaign. According to the organization, such initiatives are part of its strategy to hold government responsible for service delivery, and are sometimes supported by local municipalities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1190593/afriforum-spends-r2-5m-repairing-potholes/|title=The \u2018national pothole month\u2019 campaign saw almost 640 tons of tar used to fix 16 000 potholes across the country|date= July 5, 2016|work=citizen|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=independent >{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/south-africans-can-fix-potholes-and-charge-government-for-it-high-court/|title=South Africans can fix potholes and charge government for it. High Court|date= March 13, 2017|work=citizen|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn order to achieve this goal, AfriForum attempts to establish partnerships with municipalities.  The organisation allegedly submits wish lists to municipalities, and municipalities convert it into action plans to address issues. AfriForum says if municipalities do not cooperate in improving service delivery to residents, the organisation approaches courts to order municipalities to enforce service delivery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-statement-by-afriforum-minority-civil-organisation-brings-application-to-retain-electricity-supply-to-klerksdorp-and-jouberton-22022013-2013-02-22|title=AfriForum: Statement by AfriForum, minority civil organisation, brings application to retain electricity supply to Klerksdorp and Jouberton |date=22 February 2013|work=Polity.org.za}}</ref><ref name=independent />\n\nAn example of intervention by AfriForum in this regard, was the urgent order awarded to the organisation against the Vhembe District Municipality by the [[High Court]] in [[Pretoria]], forcing the municipality to supply water to [[Makhado]] residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/afriforum-wins-fights-for-water-1.1394477|title=Afriforum wins fights for water|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>  In a similar case in 2013, the North Gauteng High Court in Pretoria granted AfriForum an order stopping the Madibeng Municipality from cutting electricity supply to Hartbeespoort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/AfriForum-gets-order-on-Madibeng-20130315|title=AfriForum gets order on Madibeng|date=March 15, 2013|website=News24}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum's local government interventions have been described positively, even by its critics.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/MaxduPreez/afriforum-hijacking-the-afrikaner-mainstream-20160726|title=AfriForum 'hijacking the Afrikaner mainstream'|work=News24|access-date=2018-05-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Other campaigns and positions===\nAfriForum has opposed [[fracking]] in the [[Karoo]]<ref name=\"tkag\">{{cite web|title=TKAG, Afriforum become anti-fracking force |url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/73896-1021-53-TKAG_Afriforum_become_antifracking_force |publisher=The New Age Online |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116072223/http://www.thenewage.co.za/73896-1021-53-TKAG_Afriforum_become_antifracking_force |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> as well as poaching<ref name=\"iol.co.za\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/fury-as-poaching-charges-dropped-1.1270893|title=Fury as poaching charges dropped|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref> It has also campaigned against [[e-toll (South Africa)|electronic road tolling in Gauteng]].<ref name=etollsnao>{{cite web|title=E-toll notification unlawful: AfriForum |url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/Detail.aspx?news_id=71296&cat_id=1099 |publisher=The New Age Online |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116072520/http://www.thenewage.co.za/Detail.aspx?news_id=71296&cat_id=1099 |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfriForum was accepted as [[amicus curae]] (friend of the court) during a number of court cases. Cases where AfriForum acted as amicus curae, included those allowing voters overseas to vote in South African elections,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://collections.concourt.org.za/handle/20.500.12144/3574|title=Richter v Minister of Home Affairs and Others (Democratic Alliance and Others Intervening; Afriforum and Another as Ami|first=O'Regan|last=J|date=April 8, 2017|via=collections.concourt.org.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2009/3.html|title=Richter v The Minister for Home Affairs and Others (with the Democratic Alliance and Others Intervening, and with Afriforum and Another as Amici Curiae) (CCT03/09, CCT 09/09) [2009] ZACC 3; 2009 (3) SA 615 (CC) ; 2009 (5) BCLR 448 (CC) (12 March 2009)|website=www.saflii.org}}</ref> protecting mineral rights from expropriation,<ref>https://cer.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/AgiSA-v-Minister-for-Minerals-and-Energy-CC.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2013/9media.pdf</ref> and allowing public schools to promote adherence to only one or predominantly one religion during their religious school activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-04-18-00-ngo-seeks-order-declaring-adherence-to-one-religion-as-unconstitutional/|title=NGO seeks order declaring adherence to one religion at schools as unconstitutional|first=Prega|last=Govender|website=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref>http://www.saflii.org.za/za/cases/ZAGPJHC/2017/160.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.groundup.org.za/article/understanding-ogod-judgment/|title=Understanding the OGOD judgment|first=By Safura Abdool|last=Karim|date=June 29, 2017|website=GroundUp News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2017-06-29-ye-of-little-faith-court-rules-against-single-religion-schools/|title=Ye of little faith: Court rules against single-religion schools|website=TimesLIVE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloemfonteincourant.co.za/afriforum-ready-legal-battle-retain-religion-schools/|title=AfriForum ready for legal battle to retain religion in schools|first=Moeketsi|last=Mogotsi|date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> AfriForum also acted as amicus curae (later co-applicant)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sport/2019-03-06-judgement-reserved-in-the-emotive-labour-court-case-over-sports-quotas/|title=Judgement reserved in the emotive Labour Court case over sports quotas|website=SowetanLIVE}}</ref> in a case against the Minister of Sports and Recreation, and the Olympic Committee, opposing racial quotas in sport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/solidarity-challenge-quotas-in-sport-before-labour-court-20170502|title=Solidarity challenge quotas in sport before Labour Court|date=May 2, 2017|website=Sport}}</ref>\n\n==AfriForum Jeug (youth wing)==\nAfriForum's [[youth wing]] is called ''AfriForum Jeug''.<ref name=\"mgHETNslams\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-30-hten-slams-afriforums-student-race-request|title=HETN slams AfriForum's student race request|first=Bongani|last=Nkosi|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref>  It operates as a student organisation with branches at South African universities. AfriForum Jeug focuses on education issues, including mother tongue education, political interference in student affairs, and affirmative action at universities. A core objective of AfriForum Jeug is for youth to be exempted from [[affirmative action]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afriforumyouth.co.za/?page_id=13|title=Home - AfriForum Jeug|work=AfriForum Jeug}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe group's non-university activities include organising adventure camps for school learners and fundraising for children's homes. The youth wing claims that one of their biggest aims is to promote \"the Christian democratic framework\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afriforumjeug.co.za/oor-ons/|title=Oor ons}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=September 2019}}  AfriForum Jeug claims that they focus more on \"Afrikaans\" interests instead of \"Afrikaner\" interests.{{clarify|date=September 2019}}\n\nIn 2010, three AfriForum Jeug members were arrested after violating an outdoor advertising by-law to protest the proposed name change of Pretoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/3-held-for-violating-ad-by-law-20100709|title=3 held for violating ad by-law|date=2010-07-09|website=News24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a campaign against racial quotas in higher education saw AfriForum Jeug members [[blackface|paint themselves black]] to protest the alleged discrimination against 30 learners who were turned away from the [[University of Pretoria]].<ref name=dmblp>{{cite news|title=Analysis: AfriForum Youth's absurd black paint protest|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-01-30-analysis-afriforum-youths-absurd-black-paint-protest/#.UtVCefYfvMg|newspaper=Daily Maverick|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, AfriForum Jeug joined the South African Progressive Civic Organisation (Sapco), a Khoisan community, in a protest over the land rights of the indigenous group, with both minority groups feeling they have no representation in the current government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-02-22-afriforum-joins-khoisan-in-land-rights-fight|title=AfriForum joins Khoisan in land rights fight|work=dailymaverick.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013 AfriForum Jeug brought a complaint of hate speech against Jason Mfusi, leader of South African Students Congress), who on social media had posted, \"My grandfather says 'n goeie boer is 'n dooie boer\" (\"a good farmer is a dead farmer\"). An agreement by means of a mediation process, as requested by the Human Rights Commission (HRC) of the University, and Mfusi had to issue a written apology to the farming community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2013/02/07/nwu-student-in-trouble-over-facebook-posting|title=NWU student in trouble over Facebook posting|author=Tebogo Monama|work=Sowetan LIVE}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, a  campaign protesting racial quotas involved charging students of different races different prices for a cup of coffee, with white students paying R5 a cup, coloured and Indians R3, and blacks R1.<ref name=affcoffee>{{cite web|title=Afriforum Youth to offer blacks cheaper coffee|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/04/25/afriforum-youth-to-offer-blacks-cheaper-coffee|publisher=Times LIVE|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 AfriForum Jeug demanded that the [[North-West University]] reject a report into a [[Nazism|Nazi]]-style initiation ceremony at the university's Potchefstroom campus, claiming that the report discriminated against Afrikaners.<ref name=\"2014CityPressNaziReport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Archives/City-Press/Nazi-report-AfriForum-Youth-threatens-varsity-council-with-Equality-Act-20150429|title=Nazi report: AfriForum Youth threatens varsity council with Equality Act|publisher=City Press|date=2014-06-18}}</ref>  The report was originally commissioned by Minister of Higher Education and Training Blade Nzimande as an investigation into \"the initiation practices and acts of Fascism and Nazism which seem to exist at the institution\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/nwu-puk-remains-fundamentally-an-apartheid-insti-3|title=NWU: Puk remains fundamentally an apartheid institution - Blade Nzimande - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn February 2014, Flip Buys from the trade union Solidarity (which is associated with Afriforum) called for a boycott of the Afrikaans newspaper Beeld that reported that a group of Potchefstroom students gave the [[Nazi salute]] during their initiation.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maroelamedia.co.za/nuus/sa-nuus/solidariteit-bloedneus-vir-beeld-en-basson/|title=Solidariteit: Bloedneus vir Beeld en Basson|date=February 25, 2014|website=Maroela Media}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, AfriForum Youth said that allegations of racism against Curro Foundation School are themselves racist. In a statement by the organisation's chair it was said \"To portray an Afrikaans class being transported as class group falsely as racial segregation, is beyond absurd\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/curro-race-activists-should-stop-abusing-innocent-|title=Curro: Race activists should stop abusing innocent children - AfriForum Youth - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Afriforum applied to the Western Cape High Court to have posts on social media removed that stated that Afriforum supporters had \"threaten to rape women\" and had \"used rape to intimidate a rape survivor\", on the grounds that such claims are defamatory and that the claims were false.  However, the judge ruled that AfriForum protestors did in fact \"commit assault, sexual violence, sexual aggression and intimidation\" against the anti-rape culture protesters. The judge noted that while some of the statements about rape threats were not literally true, the social media poster is \"entitled to a certain amount of latitude in describing the confrontation\" due to strong emotions elicited by the issue.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>http://www1.saflii.org/za/cases/ZAWCHC/2016/175.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-rejects-damning-court-judgment-over-facebook-posts-20160710|title=AfriForum disagrees with damning court judgment over Facebook posts|date=2016-07-10|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016 eight students affiliated with AfriForum youth wing were suspended from [[Stellenbosch University]] Student Representative Council (SRC) elections after allegations of campaign irregularities. The three plaintiffs also considered some of AfriForum'sd election posters to be controversial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/8-afriforum-students-suspended-from-stellenbosch-src-elections-20160802|title=8 AfriForum students suspended from Stellenbosch SRC elections|work=News24|date=2016-08-02}}</ref>  AfriForum applied to the High Court to have the suspension overturned, and the case was eventually settled out of court.<ref>Universiteit Stellenbosch en die onverkwiklike taalstryd, Johan C Moll, Sun Press 2018, page 303</ref>  The university's student appeal court lifted the suspension one month later, stating the student court had acted outside its mandate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afriforumjeug.co.za/afriforum-jeug-vsr-kandidatuur-regmatig-herstel/|title=AfriForum Jeug VSR-kandidatuur regmatig herstel|date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, following criticism of Afriforum by a [[North-West University]] professor, Elmien du Plessis,<ref name=\"afriforumStatsDuPlessis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/GuestColumn/afriforums-own-farm-murder-stats-dont-support-their-claims-20180507|title=AfriForum's own farm murder stats don't support their claims|work=News24|date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Afriforum's deputy CEO, Ernst Roets, posted a YouTube video where he quoted [[Victor Klemperer]], stating that \"if the tables were turned after the Holocaust he \"would have all the intellectuals strung up, and the professors three feet higher than the rest; they would be left hanging from the lamp posts for as long as was compatible with hygiene.\"<ref name=\"huffPoHevyWeightAttack\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/06/afriforum-heavyweight-launches-attack-on-academic-over-criticism-about-us-tour_a_23428355/|title=AfriForum Heavyweight Launches Attack On Academic Over Criticism About US Tour|date=6 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref> Following the video posting, du Plessis and her family received threats of violence.<ref name=\"huffPoProfThreatened\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/07/professor-threatened-after-afriforum-criticism-dont-get-too-comfortable-youre-next_a_23429098/|title=Professor Threatened After AfriForum Criticism: 'Don't Get Too Comfortable, You're Next'|date=8 May 2018|publisher= Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ThreatsViolenceHanging\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/varsity-prof-on-afriforums-angry-roets-threat-of-violence-hanging-not-acceptable-20180507|title=Varsity prof on AfriForum's 'angry' Roets: 'Threat of violence, hanging not acceptable'|work=News24|date=2018-05-07}}</ref><ref name=\"habibHitsOutAfriforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/p2-academic-adam-habib-hits-out-at-disgusting-afriforum-leaders-20180510|title=Academic Adam Habib hits out at 'disgusting' AfriForum leaders|publisher=|date=2018-05-10}}</ref> A petition condemning the threats against academics was subsequently circulated.<ref name=\"huffPocademicPetitionCirculated\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/14/petition-against-afriforum-over-threat-to-academics_a_23434037/|title=Petition Against AfriForum Over Threat To Academics|date=14 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, when AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel was asked near the end of a radio interview whether he believed [[Apartheid]] was a [[Crime of apartheid|crime against humanity]], he replied by saying \"I don\u2019t think that apartheid was a crime against humanity, but I think it was wrong.\"<ref name=\"mgMay2018KrielApartheidCrime\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-05-14-i-dont-think-apartheid-was-a-crime-against-humanity-afriforums-kallie-kriel|title=I don't think apartheid was a crime against humanity \u2013 Afriforum's Kriel|first=Mashadi|last=Kekana|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"citizenKrielApartheidCrime\">{{cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/news-cns/1926171/apartheid-was-not-a-crime-afriforum/|title=Apartheid was not a crime \u2013 AfriForum|first=Robinson|last=Nqola|publisher=The Citizen}}</ref><ref name=\"702ApartheidCrimeKriel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/303461/i-dont-think-apartheid-was-a-crime-against-humanity-kriel|title=AfriForum's Kallie Kriel: I don't think apartheid was a crime against humanity|website=702}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ApartheidCrimeKriel\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apartheid-was-not-a-crime-against-humanity-afriforum-ceo-20180514|title=Apartheid was not a crime against humanity - AfriForum CEO|work=News24|date=2018-05-14}}</ref><ref name=\"iolKrielCrimeHumanity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/apartheid-no-crime-against-humanity-says-afriforums-kriel-14973712|title=Apartheid no crime against humanity, says AfriForum's Kriel|publisher=IOL News}}</ref><ref name =\"timesLiveUproarApartheid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-15-uproar-over-remark-that-apartheid-was-not-a-crime-against-humanity-by-afriforum-ceo/|title='Apartheid was not a crime against humanity': AfriForum CEO's remark sparks outrage|publisher=Times Live}}</ref><ref name=\"timesLiveWhoIsKriel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-15-who-is-afriforum-ceo-kallie-kriel/|title=Who is AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel?|publisher=Times Live}}</ref><ref name=\"iolKrielTryingToRevise\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/kriel-trying-to-revise-history-14998001|title=Kriel trying to revise history|publisher=Pretoria News}}</ref>. The organisation had previously described Apartheid as a \"so-called historical injustice\"<ref name=\"huffPoFerialMorake\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/ferial-haffajee/ferial-haffajee-tumi-morake-solidarity-and-21st-century-baasskap_a_23216514/|title=Ferial Haffajee: Tumi Morake, Solidarity And 21st Century Baasskap|date=20 September 2017|work=Huffington Post}}</ref><ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-05-15-apartheid-not-a-crime-against-humanity--afriforum-ceo/|title=Apartheid not a crime against humanity \u2013 AfriForum CEO|website=SowetanLIVE}}</ref><ref name=\"businessDayApartheidCrime\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2018-05-15-apartheid-not-a-crime-against-humanity--says-afriforum-ceo-kallie-kriel/|title=Apartheid not a crime against humanity, says AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel|publisher=Business Day}}</ref> and its deputy leader Ernst Roets has described Apartheid as a \"wooly concept\".<ref name=\"huffPoParallelState\"/>\n \nIn March 2019, AfriForum released a documentary called ''Disrupted Land'', about land reform and expropriation in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201903130571.html|title=South Africa: 'Verwoerd' Documentary Must be Retracted, Urges IRR, AfriForum Says 'Nee Wat'|first=Pieter Du|last=Toit|date=March 13, 2019|website=allAfrica.com}}</ref> In one clip, an interviewee defends HF Verwoerd's policies.  This led the Institute of Race Relations to accuse Afriforum of \"sanitising the motives behind apartheid and the brutality of its practices\" and of \"soft-soaping the evils of apartheid\".<ref name=\"news24-apartheid-irr-13032019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/verwoerd-documentary-must-retracted-urges-irr-afriforum-says-neewat-20190313|title='Verwoerd' documentary must be retracted, urges IRR, AfriForum says 'nee wat'|date=13 March 2019|work=News24}}</ref><ref name=\"bdlive-vanonselen-13032019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/opinion/columnists/2019-03-13-gareth-van-onselen-afriforums-disgraceful-and-immoral-documentary/|title=GARETH VAN ONSELEN: AfriForum\u2019s disgraceful and immoral documentary|date=13 March 2019|work=News24}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, [[Huffington Post|The Huffington Post SA]] published an editorial with several claims about AfriForum.  The press ombudsman's investigation revealed that the editor had blundered badly by assuming that AfriForum and Solidarity was the same organisation, and that claims and actions that were ascribed to AfriForum did in fact relate entirely to Solidarity.  The ombudsman rejected Huffington Post's editor's reasoning that AfriForum and Solidarity is the same organisation because among others they are both part of the \"Solidarity Movement\" and because their head offices are in the same building.  The press ombudsman ruled that Huffington Post's bungle was a \"serious breach\" of the press code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-huffington-post-sa-4205|title=AfriForum vs. Huffington Post SA|publisher=Press Council|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111524/https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-huffington-post-sa-4205|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tumi Morake: A Victim Of South Africa's 'Bell Pottinger' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/pieter-du-toit/tumi-morake-a-victim-of-south-africas-bell-pottinger_a_23207253/ |website=HuffPost South Africa |language=en |date=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn October 2010, with regard to AfriForum's response to [[Absa Group Limited|Absa Bank]] softening stance on quotas in rugby, Ferial Haffajee wrote in a column in City Press thaty \"while AfriForum is an excellent lobby group with a sense of strategy and tactics, it should be careful that its radical tactics do not dissemble into racist special pleading \u2013 a deeply conservative impulse\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/Columnists/Laager-mentality-is-a-load-of-bull-20101002/ |title=Laager mentality is a load of bull |work=News24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119232400/http://www.citypress.co.za/Columnists/Laager-mentality-is-a-load-of-bull-20101002 |archivedate=2012-11-19 }}</ref>.\n\nIn a column in July 2012, University of Cape Town Professor Pierre de Vos criticised Minister of Higher Education Blade Nzimande's \"blistering attack against the liberal notion of civil society\", and stated that the appropriate way to \"engage with organisations [such as Afriforum] is not to mutter darkly about how they are trying to take over the country by having the cheek to promote their own ideas\" but to \"criticise their ideas and the actions they take and provide arguments for why one\u2019s own ideas are better\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://constitutionallyspeaking.co.za/how-not-to-engage-in-a-battle-of-ideas/|title=How not to engage in a battle of ideas|work=constitutionallyspeaking.co.za}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has been criticized by the ruling ANC but also by many media outlets and academics. \n\nThe survivalist group Kommandokorps criticised Afriforum in February 2012, saying that Afriforum \"had not done much to prevent farm murders\".  This was in response to Afriforum's criticism of Kommandokorps in which Afriforum CEO Kallie Kriel said that Kommandokorps' treatment of young people at training camps is \"immoral and inexcusable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kommandokorps-denies-racism-20120227|title=Kommandokorps denies racism|work=News24|date=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of 2014, the [[Commission for the Promotion and Protection of the Rights of Cultural, Religious and Linguistic Communities]], criticised AfriForum's \"Save Afrikaans schools\" campaign in a press release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.za/speech/DynamicAction?pageid=461&sid=24488&tid=53893 |title=Redirecting old link |work=info.gov.za }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  The campaign followed Gauteng Department of Basic Education's decision to force three Afrikaans-medium schools in Fochville to relinquish their status as Afrikaans-medium schools at the start of the 2012 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/crlrc-meant-to-support-not-oppose-minority-rights-|title=CRLRC meant to support not oppose minority rights - AfriForum - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the [[African National Congress Youth League]] stated that AfriForum is \"the defender of white privilege\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/afriforum-defender-of-white-priviledge-ancyl-1.1313072|title=Afriforum 'defender of white privilege': ANCYL|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>, after AfriForum lodged charges of hate speech with the police and the Equality Court against ANCYL deputy president for statements relating to land held by white farmers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-06-06-lamola-hate-speech/|title=Unions to lay hate speech charges against Lamola|website=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/06/Hate-speech-case-opened-against-Lamola|title=Lamola hate speech case opened|first=Stephen|last=Grootes|website=ewn.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn a newspaper column in May 2018, [[Max du Preez]] described AfriForum's position as \"reactionary identity politics\".  He said that AfriForum \"now totally dominates the socio-political discourse among white Afrikaners\" and that they are \"sanctioned by soft editorials and columns by prominent members of the Afrikaans commentariat\".  He claimed that some Afrikaners who criticised AfriForum were \"aggressively demonised, insulted, belittled and even threatened\".<ref name=\"duPreezAfriForumDaProblem\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/MaxduPreez/the-problem-afriforum-is-causing-the-da-20180515|title=The problem AfriForum is causing the DA|work=News24|date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nIn a radio interview in May 2018, vice chancellor of the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] [[Adam Habib]] criticised AfriForum for \"linking up with fascists\" such as the French [[National Front (France)|National Front]], the Italian [[Five Star Movement]], Germany's [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]] and US president Donald Trump's national security adviser John Bolton, whom Habib referred to during the same interview as \"a known fascist\", during Kriel and Roets' 2018 world tour.<ref name=\"iolKrielTryingToRevise\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commonscat|AfriForum}}\n* {{official website|https://www.afriforum.co.za/}} {{in lang|af|en}}\n\n{{Politics of South Africa navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Civil rights organizations]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox organisation\n| name = AfriForum\n| native_name = \n| former_name = \n| image = AfriForum_logo.svg\n| image_border = \n| size = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption = \n| map = \n| msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption = \n| map2 = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = Laat jou stem hoor (English: Let your voice be heard)\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| formation = 26 March 2006<!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| founder = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| extinction = <!-- {{End date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger = \n| merged = \n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| professional_title = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters = Union Street, [[Kloofsig]], [[Centurion, Gauteng|Centurion]], [[Gauteng]]\n| location = \n| coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using {{Coord}} -->\n| region_served = \n| services = \n| membership = 235,000 (March 2020)<ref name=\"Politicsweb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/politics/meeting-with-health-minister-requested-regarding-n|title=AfriForum requests meeting with Health Minister regarding NHI|work=[[Politicsweb]]|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|author=Bester, Carina}}</ref>\n| leader_name = Kallie Kriel\n| leader_title2 = Deputy CEO\n| leader_name2 = [[Ernst Roets]]\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3 = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4 = \n| board_of_directors = \n| key_people = \n| main_organ = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = <!-- or | parent_organisation = , if one -->\n| subsidiaries = \n| affiliations = Solidarity Movement\n| budget = \n| num_staff = \n| num_volunteers = \n| slogan = \n| website = {{url|afriforum.co.za}}\n| remarks = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''AfriForum''' is a [[South Africa]]n non-governmental organisation focused on the interests of [[Afrikaners]], a subgroup of the country's [[white South Africans|white]] population. AfriForum has been described as a [[Lobbying|lobby group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahrc.org.za/index.php/sahrc-media/news/item/470-human-rights-commission-receives-complaints-against-up-afriforum|title=Human Rights Commission receives complaints against UP, Afriforum|website=www.sahrc.org.za}}</ref>, and AfriForum refers to itself as a [[Civil_and_political_rights|civil rights group]], but it has also been referred to as an Afrikaner nationalist group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1035262/self-declared-traitors-of-the-volk-trash-afriforum/|title=\u2018Traitors of the volk\u2019 trash AfriForum|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>, a white rights group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/trump-south-africa-714744/|title=Trump Is Using a White Nationalist Conspiracy Theory to Inform Policy|first1=Ryan|last1=Bort|first2=Ryan|last2=Bort|date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> and a [[White_nationalism|white nationalist group]],<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/south-africa-white-farmers-plaasmoorde-can il-ramaphosa-anc-economic-freedom-fighters-gabriel-stols-a8262306.html</ref> a description rejected by the organisation's leadership.<ref name=\u201cvoa\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/white-nationalism-moves-south-african-mainstream-politics|title=White Nationalism Moves Into South African Mainstream Politics|website=[[Voice of America]]}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 2006 to encourage the re-engagement of Afrikaners in the public sphere,<ref name=visser>{{cite web|last=Visser |first=Wessel P |title=From MWU To Solidarity \u2013 A Trade Union Reinventing Itself |url=http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departemente1/geskiedenis/docs/from_mwu_to_solidarity.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=University Of Stellenbosch |accessdate=14 January 2014 |page=20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811050629/http://sun025.sun.ac.za/portal/page/portal/Arts/Departemente1/geskiedenis/docs/from_mwu_to_solidarity.pdf |archivedate=11 August 2013 }}</ref> it is closely affiliated to the [[Solidarity_(South_African_trade_union)|Solidarity]] [[trade union]],<ref name=\"huffPoParallelState\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/01/31/afriforum-and-solidaritys-parallel-state_a_21704173/|title=AfriForum And Solidarity's 'Parallel State'|date=31 January 2017|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref> and has attracted significant controversy because of a statement that [[Apartheid]] was not a [[Crimes against humanity|crime against humanity]].<ref name=\"timesLiveUproarApartheid\"/><ref name=\"bdlive-vanonselen-13032019\"/><ref name=\"news24-apartheid-irr-13032019\"/>  A court however ruled that \u201cKriel did not justify Apartheid or align himself with the racial discriminatory policies of the past. He stated unequivocally that Apartheid was wrong and that it was a system that infringed on the dignity of people\u201d. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/447418684/Black-First-Land-First-v-AfriForum-Kallie-Kriel-EQ-6-2018-Judgment-29-Oct-2019|title=Black First Land First v AfriForum & Kallie Kriel (EQ 6/2018) Judgment (29 Oct 2019)|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/10/29/afriforum-s-kriel-court-win-against-blf-proves-i-m-not-a-supporter-of-apartheid|title=AfriForum's Kriel: Court win against BLF proves I'm not a supporter of apartheid|last=Dlulane|first=Bonga|website=ewn.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  \n\nAfriForum is sometimes accused of advancing the idea of a [[White_genocide_conspiracy_theory|white genocide]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45336840|title=The groups playing on the fears of a 'white genocide\u2019|last=Chothia|first=Farouk|date=2018-09-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> with the organisation denying this, and lodging multiple successful complaints against media reporting that claimed it promotes the idea of a white genocide.<ref>{{cite web |title=[UPDATE] 'We have never ever said there is a white genocide happening in SA' |url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/316863/we-have-never-ever-said-there-is-a-white-genocide-happening-in-sa |website=702 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |language=en |date=27 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-mail--guardian-4366|title=AfriForum vs. Mail & Guardian|publisher=Press Council|access-date=2019-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302005952/https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-mail--guardian-4366|archive-date=2019-03-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAfriForum was founded in 2006 following public consultations about its charter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180326/http://www.afriforum.co.za/mediaverklarings.htm|title=AfriForum : Media|date=September 28, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180249/http://www.afriforum.co.za/dokumente.htm|title=AfriForum : Media|date=September 28, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>  In the preface to the charter, AfriForum refers to itself as a \u201ccitizen's right initiative founded by the trade union Solidarity\u201d.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20060928180945/http://www.afriforum.co.za/dokumente/09 2006 voorwoord - burgerregte-manifes.doc</ref>\n\nBy March 2020 AfriForum had 235 000 contributing members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/politics/meeting-with-health-minister-requested-regarding-n|title=AfriForum requests meeting with Health Minister regarding NHI - POLITICS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIts leader, Kallie Kriel, was previously a member of the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]], and a leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus]] (FF+) youth wing, and a large number of its executive leadership were formerly associated with Freedom Front Plus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thoughtleader.co.za/thornegodinho/2014/01/08/afriforum-and-the-rise-of-the-new-right/|title=AfriForum and the rise of the new right &#124; Thought Leader}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns, policies and projects==\n[[File:AfriForum - Standerton-betoging.jpg|thumb|left|AfriForum protest outside the [[Pretoria High Court]]]]\n\n===Crime and corruption===\n====Farm attacks====\nAfriForum has been a vocal critic of the [[ANC]]'s response to [[South African farm attacks]], claiming that the party bears a responsibility for \"remain[ing] silent\" about the violence,<ref name=blamfm>{{cite web|title=AfriForum blames ANC for farm murders|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2012/09/12/afriforum-blames-anc-for-farm-murders|publisher=Times LIVE|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> and lodging a complaint to the [[South African Human Rights Commission]] against the [[Department of Police (South Africa)|Police Minister]] for failing to do enough to protect farmers.<ref name=farmiol>{{cite web|title=Afriforum takes farm murders to SAHRC|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/afriforum-takes-farm-murders-to-sahrc-1.1524798|publisher=IOL.co.za|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> The organisation launched the book ''Kill the Boer''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.killtheboerbook.com/reviews/|title=Reviews - Kill the Boer Book|work=Kill the Boer Book|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> written by [[Ernst Roets]], the organisation's deputy CEO.<ref name=\"Hlatshaneni\">{{cite news |last1=Hlatshaneni |first1=Simnikiwe |title=Outrage surrounds book claiming top ANC officials \u2018killed the boer\u2019 |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1964479/outrage-surrounds-book-claiming-top-anc-officials-killed-the-boer/ |accessdate=24 November 2018 |newspaper=[[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]] |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation also launched the Wilmien Potgieter Fund to assist children who were victims of farm attacks often resulting in the loss of one or both parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/en/farm-attacks-increase-farm-murders-decrease/|title=Farm attacks increase, but farm murders decrease|last=AfriForum|date=2019-01-29|website=AfriForum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\n====Private prosecutions====\nThe organisation formed a [[private prosecution]]s unit, headed by well-known former state prosecutor [[Gerrie Nel]], amid allegations that the [[National Prosecuting Authority]] (NPA) was selective in prosecutions, and politically biased.<ref name=\"conversationHowPrivateProsecutionsWillWork\">{{Cite news|url=https://theconversation.com/explainer-how-south-africas-first-private-prosecutions-unit-will-work-72389|title=Explainer: how South Africa's first private prosecutions unit will work|last=Feldhaus|first=Chantelle|work=[[The Conversation]]|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> \n\n[[Grace Mugabe]], the wife of [[Robert Mugabe]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/gerrie-nel-takes-on-grace-mugabe-will-assist-alleged-assault-victim/ | title=Gerrie Nel takes on Grace Mugabe, announces plan to assist alleged assault victim| date=2017-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nehandaradio.com/2017/08/17/gerrie-nel-sets-sights-grace-mugabe/|title=Gerrie Nel sets sights on Grace Mugabe \u2013 Nehanda Radio|date=2017-08-17|work=Nehanda Radio|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/as-gerrie-nel-targets-grace-mugabe-we-remember-the-bulldogs-biggest-cases/ | title=As Gerrie Nel targets Grace Mugabe, we remember the bulldog's biggest cases| date=2017-08-18}}</ref> and [[Duduzane Zuma]], son of then-President [[Jacob Zuma]], were targeted by the unit for prosecution after the NPA showed reluctance to prosecute them for assault, and [[culpable homicide]], respectively.<ref name=\"ewnBLfConfrontKriel\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/12/blf-confront-afriforum-s-kriel-after-duduzane-zuma-court-appearance | title=BLF confront AfriForum's Kriel after Duduzane Zuma court appearance}}</ref> Following AfriForum's move to privately prosecute Zuma, the National Prosecuting Authority decided to pursue a prosecution instead.<ref name=\"ewnStrongCaseZuma\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/12/gerrie-nel-afriforum-has-strong-case-against-duduzane-zuma | title=Gerrie Nel: AfriForum has strong case against Duduzane Zuma}}</ref> The organisation also undertook a prosecution of the chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]], [[Thandi Modise]], after allegations of [[animal cruelty]] at her [[North West (South Africa)|North West]] farm.<ref name=\"encaScoresModise\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.enca.com/scores-dead-animals-found-thandi-modises-farm | title=Scores of dead animals found on Thandi Modise's farm}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ToProsecuteModise\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-to-privately-prosecute-thandi-modise-20180719 | title=AfriForum to privately prosecute Thandi Modise over animal cruelty| date=2018-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"ewnTakeOnCruelty\">{{Cite web | url=http://ewn.co.za/2018/07/19/afriforum-to-take-on-thandi-modise-for-animal-cruelty | title=AfriForum to privately prosecute Thandi Modise for animal cruelty}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, AfriForum undertook a private prosecution of EFF leader [[Julius Malema]] on charges of fraud and corruption, after the NPA failed to continue prosecuting the case.<ref name=\"iolMalemaAfriForumExplainsCase\"/> AfriForum had initially laid the charges against Malema in 2011.<ref name=\"iolMalemaAfriForumExplainsCase\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/why-prosecute-malema-afriforum-explains-its-case-14536130|title=Why prosecute Malema? AfriForum explains its case - IOL News|publisher=}}</ref> It also exerted pressure on authorities to investigate and prosecute Malema for discharging a firearm at a rally in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/malema-receiving-preferential-treatment-npa-claims-lobby-group/|title=Malema receiving preferential treatment from NPA, claims lobby group|website=Jacaranda FM}}</ref>\n\n===Education, language and culture===\nAfriForum has strongly opposed the proposed renaming of South Africa's capital from [[Pretoria]] to Tshwane, as well as street renaming in Pretoria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/81-against-Pretoria-name-change-20130414|title=81% against Pretoria name change|work=News24|date=2013-04-14}}</ref> \n\nThe organisation campaigns to promote mother tongue education<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/01/17/afrikaans-schools-have-a-right-to-be-here-afriforum_a_23335475/|title='Afrikaans Schools Have A Right To Be Here' -- AfriForum|date=2018-01-17|work=HuffPost South Africa|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-ZA}}</ref> and keep religion in schools.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2017-06-28-mixed-reaction-to-courts-ruling-against-single-religion-schools/|title=Mixed reaction to court\u2019s ruling against single-religion schools|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-afriforum-ready-for-legal-battle-to-keep-religion-in-schools-2016-02-24|title=AfriForum: AfriForum ready for legal battle to keep religion in schools|website=Polity.org.za}}</ref> and has clashed with Gauteng MEC for Basic Education [[Panyaza Lesufi]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://city-press.news24.com/News/youre-defending-your-territory-not-a-language-lesufi-tells-afriforum-20160602|title=You\u2019re defending your territory, not a language, Lesufi tells AfriForum|work=CityPress|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref> who the organisation perceives as being hostile to [[Afrikaans in schools]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/en/afriforum-welcomes-panyaza-lesufis-move-education/|title=AfriForum welcomes Panyaza Lesufi\u2019s move from education|date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> because of proposed school regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/let-me-be-clear-i-will-make-no-apology-lesufi-responds-to-ff-plus-on-afrikaans-schools-20181026|title='Let me be clear, I will make no apology' - Lesufi responds to FF Plus on Afrikaans schools|date=October 26, 2018|website=News24}}</ref> {{clarify|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn 2008, Afriforum laid a charge of attempting to defeat the ends of justice against a senior superintendent of the SAPS forensics laboratory in Pretoria who refused to receive evidence in over 50 cases (including murder and rape) because the covering letter was in Afrikaans.<ref name=tra>{{cite web|last1=Trapido |first1=Michael |title=No country for Afrikaans then? |url=http://www.thoughtleader.co.za/traps/2008/07/16/petty-apartheid-revisited/|website=[[Thought Leader]] |publisher=Mail&Guardian |date = July 16, 2008 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Land===\n{{see|Land reform in South Africa}}\nAfriForum is involved in issues regarding [[land reform in South Africa|land reform]], blaming the \"corruption\" and \"incompetence\" of the [[Department of Rural Development and Land Reform]] for the slow pace of land reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821115109/http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2012/06/27/afriforum-slams-zuma-land-comments|title=AfriForum slams Zuma land comments |publisher= Times LIVE|date=August 21, 2014|via=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum has assisted black landowners who were victims of [[squatting|squatters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/mobi/Detail.aspx?NewsID=47994&CatID=1009 |title=Eviction order for land invaders given go-ahead |work=thenewage.co.za |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821041728/http://www.thenewage.co.za/mobi/Detail.aspx?NewsID=47994&CatID=1009 |archivedate=2014-08-21 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/southafrica/news/pretoria-land-invasion-case-continues-20120202|title=Pretoria land invasion case continues|date=February 2, 2012|website=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/southafrica/news/pretoria-land-invaders-ordered-to-move-20120202|title=Pretoria land invaders ordered to move|date=February 2, 2012|website=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/party/bank-accounts-of-wallmansthal-land-grabber-frozen-|title=Bank accounts of Wallmansthal land grabber frozen - AfriForum - PARTY &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.za/department-hand-over-title-deeds-wallmansthal-and-berlin-mission-claimants|title=Department to hand over title deeds to Wallmansthal and Berlin mission claimants &#124; South African Government|website=www.gov.za}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation appeared before a parliamentary committee to oppose proposed constitutional amendments to allow for expropriation without compensation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/you-are-drunk-on-the-ideology-of-the-ndr--ernst-ro|title=You are drunk on the ideology of the NDR - Ernst Roets - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2018-09-06-afriforum-bemoans-fallacy-that-whites-stole-the-land/|title=AfriForum bemoans \u2018fallacy that whites stole the land\u2019|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> and, in August 2018, AfriForum controversially published a list of farms that are said to be targeted by the government for expropriation without compensation that the organisation received from an anonymous source.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/this-is-the-list-of-farms-targeted-for-ewc--afrifo|title=This is the list of farms targeted for EWC - AfriForum - DOCUMENTS {{!}} Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za|language=en|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> Although the organisation received a backlash from some organisations and political parties regarding the legitimacy of the list, the South African Institute for Race Relations confirmed and corroborated the legitimacy of the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/land-expropriation-list-released-by-afriforum-is-legitimate-irr-20180814|title='Land expropriation list released by AfriForum is legitimate' \u2013 IRR|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum successfully complained about a column published on [[News24]] by journalist [[Pieter du Toit]] regarding its testimony before the parliamentary committee discussing amending the constitution to allow for expropriation without compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115215150/http://www.presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-news24-4356|title=AfriForum vs. News24|publisher=Press Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Apology to AfriForum for 'no solutions' claim in land column |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-afriforum-for-no-solutions-claim-in-land-column-20181116 |website=News24 |language=en |date=16 November 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Racism and hate speech campaigns===\nIn April 2011, AfriForum opened a civil case against [[Julius Malema]], in the [[Equality Court]] after he sang the words \u201cdubul\u2019 ibhunu\u201d, which translates as \u201c[[Dubul' ibhunu|shoot the boer]]\u201d, at ANC Youth League gatherings.<ref>Benesch, Susan (2012). \"Words as Weapons\". World Policy Journal. 29 (1): 7\u201312. doi:10.1177/0740277512443794. JSTOR 41510486.</ref><ref name=shtbs>{{cite news|title=ANC youth leader denies hatred in 'Shoot the boer' song|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/20/julius-malema-hate-speech-boer|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=2011-04-20|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> It was ruled that the song constituted [[hate speech]] and undermined the dignity of Afrikaners, and was discriminatory and harmful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2011-09-12-shoot-the-boer-its-hate-speech-says-judge|title='Shoot the boer': It's hate speech, says judge|author=Staff Reporter, Sapa-AFP|work=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref name=stbban>{{cite news|title=ANC Julius Malema's Shoot the Boer ruled 'hate speech'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14878102|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2014|date=2011-09-12}}</ref> In 2012, AfriForum and the ANC reached a settlement before the appeal case was due to be argued in the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]] (SCA) in [[Bloemfontein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Shoot-the-Boer-appeal-canned-20121031-2|title=Shoot the Boer appeal canned|work=News24|date=2012-10-31}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum has laid criminal charges against other political figures,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/hate-speech-charge-laid-against-lamola-20120709-2/ |title=Hate speech charge laid against Lamola |work=News24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211202232/http://www.citypress.co.za/politics/hate-speech-charge-laid-against-lamola-20120709-2/ |archivedate=2012-12-11 }}</ref> and social media users that it deemed to be inciting violence and racism,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1510149/afriforum-lay-hate-charges-facebooker/|title=AfriForum lays hate speech charges against \u2018kill pink pigs\u2019 Facebooker|last=|first=|date=|website=citizen.co.za|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> In June the same year, AfriForum said that they plan to lay criminal charges against 100 social media users for incitement of violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1554475/afriforum-to-lay-charges-against-these-100-social-media-users/|title=AfriForum to lay charges against these 100 social media users|last=reporter|first=Citizen|work=The Citizen|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-lays-criminal-charges-against-police-officials-2018-06-18|title=AfriForum lays criminal charges against police officials|work=Polity.org.za|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/sandf-member-caught-in-alleged-race-row-with-civilian-18801565|title=SANDF member caught in alleged race row with civilian &#124; Cape Times|website=www.iol.co.za}}</ref> and created a unit against racism and hate speech.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-launches-anti-racism-unit-20170911|title=AfriForum launches anti-racism unit|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afriforum.co.za/afriforum-stig-teenrassisme-eenheid-2/|title=AfriForum stig teenrassisme-eenheid|date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> It also addressed racist incidents involving a number of people,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/south-africans-have-double-standards-when-it-comes-to-racism-afriforum-20170216|title=South Africans have double standards when it comes to racism|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2011/09/08/AfriForum-welcomes-Darren-Scotts-apology|title=AfriForum welcomes Darren Scott's apology|last=News|first=Eyewitness|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> Dan Roodt,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/AfriForum-condemns-racist-Dan-Roodt-20141113|title=AfriForum condemns 'racist' Dan Roodt|date=2014-11-13|access-date=2018-09-26|work=News24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-22-afriforum-condemns-use-of-k-word-by-catzavelos-urges-consistency-in-condemnation-of-racism-from-all-sides/|title=AfriForum condemns use of k-word by Catzavelos\u201a urges consistency in condemnation of racism from all sides|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> and the paramilitary [[Kommandokorps]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kommandokorps-denies-racism-20120227|title=Kommandokorps denies racism|work=News24|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> and has stated that it regards the use of the 'k-word' [[Kaffir (racial term)|kaffir]] to be a \"gross human rights violation\".<ref name=sabckword>{{cite web|title=AfriForum reaffirm stance on use of K-word amid racist saga|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/aa9441804fe8018d8628e60b5d39e4bb/AfriForum-reaffirm-stance-on-use-of-K-word-amid-racist-saga|publisher=SABC News|accessdate=14 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116083121/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/aa9441804fe8018d8628e60b5d39e4bb/AfriForum-reaffirm-stance-on-use-of-K-word-amid-racist-saga|archive-date=16 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nAfriforum opposed restrictions imposed by the Equality Court in 2019 on the \"gratuitous display\" of the [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|old South African flag]], claiming that such restrictions limited freedom of speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/afriforum-says-apartheid-flag-ruling-is-setback-for-freedom-of-speech-31059834|title=AfriForum says apartheid flag ruling is setback for freedom of speech &#124; IOL News|website=www.iol.co.za}}</ref>\n\n===Minority rights===\nAfriForum has engaged with the [[United Nations]] on minority rights issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/Minority/Pages/Session8OralWrittenStatements.aspx|title=OHCHR &#124; Oral statements delivered at the Forum/Written Submissions during the 8th session|website=www.ohchr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.ohchr.org/results.aspx?k=afriforum|title=Search Center|website=search.ohchr.org}}</ref> and has criticised the ruling ANC about what it claims is a denial of minority rights in the country.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} However, ''[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]'' journalist [[Adriaan Basson]] has accused the organisation of overreacting to the situation regarding minority rights. Basson stated in an open letter to AfriForum CEO, Kallie Kriel, that the premise of AfriForum's campaigns is one of victimhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Columnists/GuestColumn/White-first-African-second-20110926|title=White first. African second|work=News24|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>  Subsequent to Basson's open letter, president Jacob Zuma told the national assembly that \"You have more rights because you're a majority; you have less rights because you're a minority. That's how democracy works\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/You-dont-understand-democracy-Zuma-told-20120914|title=You don't understand democracy, Zuma told|date=2012-09-14|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===International lobbying===\nAfriforum claimed credit for taking an [[Australia]]n journalist on a tour of South Africa, and for the \"dozens\" of articles detailing violent attacks on farms that subsequently appeared in the Australian media.<ref name=\"forumNuusUsaTour\">{{cite web|url=https://forumnuus.co.za/afriforum-se-kriel-en-roets-na-vsa-vir-bewusmaking-oor-plaasmoorde-en-onteiening/|title=AfriForum se Kriel en Roets na VSA vir bewusmaking oor plaasmoorde en onteiening|trans-title=Afriforum's Kriel and Roets travel to USA to raise awareness of farm murders and expropriation|quote= After an Australian journalist visiting South Africa was taken on a tour of South Africa by Afriforum, literally dozens of articles appeared in the Australian media about farm murders and the ANC government's misjudgment on property rights |publisher=Forum Nuus|date=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"huffPoDuToirPlayingWithFire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/pieter-du-toit/afriforums-u-s-adventure-playing-with-fire-after-setting-australia-alight_a_23426470/|title=AfriForum's U.S. Adventure: Playing With Fire, Just Like In Oz|date=4 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref><ref name=\"southAfricaAntiWhiteFrankChung\"/><ref name=\"smhDigIn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/africa/white-south-african-farmers-dig-in-against-deadly-persecution-20180317-p4z4vx.html|title=White South African farmers dig in against deadly 'persecution'|date=17 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inquirer/six-hours-of-torture-for-the-keys-to-an-empty-safe/news-story/2497280df1b18c31f55344d9f2dcf8f4|title=Killed because you're white|date=17 March 2018|newspaper=The Australian}}</ref><ref name=\"southAfricaAntiWhiteFrankChung\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/world-economy/south-africans-trapped-like-frogs-in-boiling-water-as-racial-violence-escalates/news-story/6882cebcd8d518cf949bb861b617d8ac|title=It is a very, very violent country|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"smhDigIn\"/>\n\nAfriForum also undertook a tour of the United States that included meetings with [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]], staffers for Senator [[Ted Cruz]], and an interview on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"ajLobbyingUnderFire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/south-african-group-fire-lobbying-white-rights-180514054424008.html|title=South African group under fire for lobbying US for white rights|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> AfriForum toured Australia in October 2018 to raise awareness of farm attacks. Ian Cameron from AfriForum was interviewed on [[Sky News Australia]]'s program [[Outsiders (Australian TV program)|Outsiders]] by [[Ross Cameron]] and Rowan Dean.<ref name=\"mailAndGuardian20181015\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-10-15-afriforum-decries-sa-farm-murders-down-under|title=AfriForum decries SA farm murders down under|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref> AfriForum also met Australian MP [[Andrew Hastie (politician)|Andrew Hastie]] and delivered a presentation before the [[Parliament of Western Australia]].<ref name=\"timesLive20181005\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-10-14-afriforum-in-australia-to-talk-about-farm-attacks-and-murders-in-sa/|title=AfriForum in Australia to talk about farm attacks and murders in SA|publisher=Times Live}}</ref>\n\n====Zimbabwe====\nThe group contested the presence of [[Robert Mugabe]] at the 2009 inauguration of [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref name=gsd>{{cite news|title=Great song and dance as Zuma is sworn in as president of South Africa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/may/07/south-africa-zuma-president-inauguration|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=14 January 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2009-05-07|last1=Correspondent|first1=David Smith Africa}}</ref> It was also involved in a bid to prevent the delivery of [[Alouette III]] Air Force helicopters to the [[Zimbabwe Army|Zimbabwean army]].<ref name=zimheli>{{cite news|title=AfriForum wins bid to halt Zim helicopter delivery|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-01-26-afriforum-wins-bid-to-halt-zim-helicopter-delivery|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 a legal team for AfriForum representing farmers in [[Zimbabwe]] won a court bid to sue Zimbabwe's government over its \u201ccruel\u201d and \u201cvengeful\u201d [[expropriation]] of South African-owned farms. In 2008 the regional court SADC tribunal ruled that [[Zimbabwe's land reform]] was illegal and racist, and that those who had suffered discrimination by having their farms expropriated had the right to compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/afriforum-wins-first-round-in-zimbabwe-case-1.470355|title=Afriforum wins first round in Zimbabwe case|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nAfriForum encourages communities to become self-sufficient. Activities undertaken have included a pothole fixing campaign. According to the organization, such initiatives are part of its strategy to hold government responsible for service delivery, and are sometimes supported by local municipalities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1190593/afriforum-spends-r2-5m-repairing-potholes/|title=The \u2018national pothole month\u2019 campaign saw almost 640 tons of tar used to fix 16 000 potholes across the country|date= July 5, 2016|work=citizen|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=independent >{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/south-africans-can-fix-potholes-and-charge-government-for-it-high-court/|title=South Africans can fix potholes and charge government for it. High Court|date= March 13, 2017|work=citizen|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn order to achieve this goal, AfriForum attempts to establish partnerships with municipalities.  The organisation allegedly submits wish lists to municipalities, and municipalities convert it into action plans to address issues. AfriForum says if municipalities do not cooperate in improving service delivery to residents, the organisation approaches courts to order municipalities to enforce service delivery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polity.org.za/article/afriforum-statement-by-afriforum-minority-civil-organisation-brings-application-to-retain-electricity-supply-to-klerksdorp-and-jouberton-22022013-2013-02-22|title=AfriForum: Statement by AfriForum, minority civil organisation, brings application to retain electricity supply to Klerksdorp and Jouberton |date=22 February 2013|work=Polity.org.za}}</ref><ref name=independent />\n\nAn example of intervention by AfriForum in this regard, was the urgent order awarded to the organisation against the Vhembe District Municipality by the [[High Court]] in [[Pretoria]], forcing the municipality to supply water to [[Makhado]] residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/afriforum-wins-fights-for-water-1.1394477|title=Afriforum wins fights for water|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>  In a similar case in 2013, the North Gauteng High Court in Pretoria granted AfriForum an order stopping the Madibeng Municipality from cutting electricity supply to Hartbeespoort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/AfriForum-gets-order-on-Madibeng-20130315|title=AfriForum gets order on Madibeng|date=March 15, 2013|website=News24}}</ref>\n\nAfriForum's local government interventions have been described positively, even by its critics.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/MaxduPreez/afriforum-hijacking-the-afrikaner-mainstream-20160726|title=AfriForum 'hijacking the Afrikaner mainstream'|work=News24|access-date=2018-05-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Other campaigns and positions===\nAfriForum has opposed [[fracking]] in the [[Karoo]]<ref name=\"tkag\">{{cite web|title=TKAG, Afriforum become anti-fracking force |url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/73896-1021-53-TKAG_Afriforum_become_antifracking_force |publisher=The New Age Online |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116072223/http://www.thenewage.co.za/73896-1021-53-TKAG_Afriforum_become_antifracking_force |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> as well as poaching<ref name=\"iol.co.za\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/crime-courts/fury-as-poaching-charges-dropped-1.1270893|title=Fury as poaching charges dropped|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref> It has also campaigned against [[e-toll (South Africa)|electronic road tolling in Gauteng]].<ref name=etollsnao>{{cite web|title=E-toll notification unlawful: AfriForum |url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/Detail.aspx?news_id=71296&cat_id=1099 |publisher=The New Age Online |accessdate=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116072520/http://www.thenewage.co.za/Detail.aspx?news_id=71296&cat_id=1099 |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfriForum was accepted as [[amicus curae]] (friend of the court) during a number of court cases. Cases where AfriForum acted as amicus curae, included those allowing voters overseas to vote in South African elections,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://collections.concourt.org.za/handle/20.500.12144/3574|title=Richter v Minister of Home Affairs and Others (Democratic Alliance and Others Intervening; Afriforum and Another as Ami|first=O'Regan|last=J|date=April 8, 2017|via=collections.concourt.org.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2009/3.html|title=Richter v The Minister for Home Affairs and Others (with the Democratic Alliance and Others Intervening, and with Afriforum and Another as Amici Curiae) (CCT03/09, CCT 09/09) [2009] ZACC 3; 2009 (3) SA 615 (CC) ; 2009 (5) BCLR 448 (CC) (12 March 2009)|website=www.saflii.org}}</ref> protecting mineral rights from expropriation,<ref>https://cer.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/AgiSA-v-Minister-for-Minerals-and-Energy-CC.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2013/9media.pdf</ref> and allowing public schools to promote adherence to only one or predominantly one religion during their religious school activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-04-18-00-ngo-seeks-order-declaring-adherence-to-one-religion-as-unconstitutional/|title=NGO seeks order declaring adherence to one religion at schools as unconstitutional|first=Prega|last=Govender|website=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref>http://www.saflii.org.za/za/cases/ZAGPJHC/2017/160.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.groundup.org.za/article/understanding-ogod-judgment/|title=Understanding the OGOD judgment|first=By Safura Abdool|last=Karim|date=June 29, 2017|website=GroundUp News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2017-06-29-ye-of-little-faith-court-rules-against-single-religion-schools/|title=Ye of little faith: Court rules against single-religion schools|website=TimesLIVE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloemfonteincourant.co.za/afriforum-ready-legal-battle-retain-religion-schools/|title=AfriForum ready for legal battle to retain religion in schools|first=Moeketsi|last=Mogotsi|date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> AfriForum also acted as amicus curae (later co-applicant)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sport/2019-03-06-judgement-reserved-in-the-emotive-labour-court-case-over-sports-quotas/|title=Judgement reserved in the emotive Labour Court case over sports quotas|website=SowetanLIVE}}</ref> in a case against the Minister of Sports and Recreation, and the Olympic Committee, opposing racial quotas in sport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/solidarity-challenge-quotas-in-sport-before-labour-court-20170502|title=Solidarity challenge quotas in sport before Labour Court|date=May 2, 2017|website=Sport}}</ref>\n\n==AfriForum Jeug (youth wing)==\nAfriForum's [[youth wing]] is called ''AfriForum Jeug''.<ref name=\"mgHETNslams\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2013-09-30-hten-slams-afriforums-student-race-request|title=HETN slams AfriForum's student race request|first=Bongani|last=Nkosi|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref>  It operates as a student organisation with branches at South African universities. AfriForum Jeug focuses on education issues, including mother tongue education, political interference in student affairs, and affirmative action at universities. A core objective of AfriForum Jeug is for youth to be exempted from [[affirmative action]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afriforumyouth.co.za/?page_id=13|title=Home - AfriForum Jeug|work=AfriForum Jeug}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe group's non-university activities include organising adventure camps for school learners and fundraising for children's homes. The youth wing claims that one of their biggest aims is to promote \"the Christian democratic framework\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afriforumjeug.co.za/oor-ons/|title=Oor ons}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=September 2019}}  AfriForum Jeug claims that they focus more on \"Afrikaans\" interests instead of \"Afrikaner\" interests.{{clarify|date=September 2019}}\n\nIn 2010, three AfriForum Jeug members were arrested after violating an outdoor advertising by-law to protest the proposed name change of Pretoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/3-held-for-violating-ad-by-law-20100709|title=3 held for violating ad by-law|date=2010-07-09|website=News24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a campaign against racial quotas in higher education saw AfriForum Jeug members [[blackface|paint themselves black]] to protest the alleged discrimination against 30 learners who were turned away from the [[University of Pretoria]].<ref name=dmblp>{{cite news|title=Analysis: AfriForum Youth's absurd black paint protest|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-01-30-analysis-afriforum-youths-absurd-black-paint-protest/#.UtVCefYfvMg|newspaper=Daily Maverick|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, AfriForum Jeug joined the South African Progressive Civic Organisation (Sapco), a Khoisan community, in a protest over the land rights of the indigenous group, with both minority groups feeling they have no representation in the current government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-02-22-afriforum-joins-khoisan-in-land-rights-fight|title=AfriForum joins Khoisan in land rights fight|work=dailymaverick.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013 AfriForum Jeug brought a complaint of hate speech against Jason Mfusi, leader of South African Students Congress), who on social media had posted, \"My grandfather says 'n goeie boer is 'n dooie boer\" (\"a good farmer is a dead farmer\"). An agreement by means of a mediation process, as requested by the Human Rights Commission (HRC) of the University, and Mfusi had to issue a written apology to the farming community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2013/02/07/nwu-student-in-trouble-over-facebook-posting|title=NWU student in trouble over Facebook posting|author=Tebogo Monama|work=Sowetan LIVE}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, a  campaign protesting racial quotas involved charging students of different races different prices for a cup of coffee, with white students paying R5 a cup, coloured and Indians R3, and blacks R1.<ref name=affcoffee>{{cite web|title=Afriforum Youth to offer blacks cheaper coffee|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2013/04/25/afriforum-youth-to-offer-blacks-cheaper-coffee|publisher=Times LIVE|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 AfriForum Jeug demanded that the [[North-West University]] reject a report into a [[Nazism|Nazi]]-style initiation ceremony at the university's Potchefstroom campus, claiming that the report discriminated against Afrikaners.<ref name=\"2014CityPressNaziReport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Archives/City-Press/Nazi-report-AfriForum-Youth-threatens-varsity-council-with-Equality-Act-20150429|title=Nazi report: AfriForum Youth threatens varsity council with Equality Act|publisher=City Press|date=2014-06-18}}</ref>  The report was originally commissioned by Minister of Higher Education and Training Blade Nzimande as an investigation into \"the initiation practices and acts of Fascism and Nazism which seem to exist at the institution\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/nwu-puk-remains-fundamentally-an-apartheid-insti-3|title=NWU: Puk remains fundamentally an apartheid institution - Blade Nzimande - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn February 2014, Flip Buys from the trade union Solidarity (which is associated with Afriforum) called for a boycott of the Afrikaans newspaper Beeld that reported that a group of Potchefstroom students gave the [[Nazi salute]] during their initiation.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maroelamedia.co.za/nuus/sa-nuus/solidariteit-bloedneus-vir-beeld-en-basson/|title=Solidariteit: Bloedneus vir Beeld en Basson|date=February 25, 2014|website=Maroela Media}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, AfriForum Youth said that allegations of racism against Curro Foundation School are themselves racist. In a statement by the organisation's chair it was said \"To portray an Afrikaans class being transported as class group falsely as racial segregation, is beyond absurd\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/curro-race-activists-should-stop-abusing-innocent-|title=Curro: Race activists should stop abusing innocent children - AfriForum Youth - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Afriforum applied to the Western Cape High Court to have posts on social media removed that stated that Afriforum supporters had \"threaten to rape women\" and had \"used rape to intimidate a rape survivor\", on the grounds that such claims are defamatory and that the claims were false.  However, the judge ruled that AfriForum protestors did in fact \"commit assault, sexual violence, sexual aggression and intimidation\" against the anti-rape culture protesters. The judge noted that while some of the statements about rape threats were not literally true, the social media poster is \"entitled to a certain amount of latitude in describing the confrontation\" due to strong emotions elicited by the issue.<ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>http://www1.saflii.org/za/cases/ZAWCHC/2016/175.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/afriforum-rejects-damning-court-judgment-over-facebook-posts-20160710|title=AfriForum disagrees with damning court judgment over Facebook posts|date=2016-07-10|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016 eight students affiliated with AfriForum youth wing were suspended from [[Stellenbosch University]] Student Representative Council (SRC) elections after allegations of campaign irregularities. The three plaintiffs also considered some of AfriForum'sd election posters to be controversial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/8-afriforum-students-suspended-from-stellenbosch-src-elections-20160802|title=8 AfriForum students suspended from Stellenbosch SRC elections|work=News24|date=2016-08-02}}</ref>  AfriForum applied to the High Court to have the suspension overturned, and the case was eventually settled out of court.<ref>Universiteit Stellenbosch en die onverkwiklike taalstryd, Johan C Moll, Sun Press 2018, page 303</ref>  The university's student appeal court lifted the suspension one month later, stating the student court had acted outside its mandate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afriforumjeug.co.za/afriforum-jeug-vsr-kandidatuur-regmatig-herstel/|title=AfriForum Jeug VSR-kandidatuur regmatig herstel|date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, following criticism of Afriforum by a [[North-West University]] professor, Elmien du Plessis,<ref name=\"afriforumStatsDuPlessis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/GuestColumn/afriforums-own-farm-murder-stats-dont-support-their-claims-20180507|title=AfriForum's own farm murder stats don't support their claims|work=News24|date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Afriforum's deputy CEO, Ernst Roets, posted a YouTube video where he quoted [[Victor Klemperer]], stating that \"if the tables were turned after the Holocaust he \"would have all the intellectuals strung up, and the professors three feet higher than the rest; they would be left hanging from the lamp posts for as long as was compatible with hygiene.\"<ref name=\"huffPoHevyWeightAttack\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/06/afriforum-heavyweight-launches-attack-on-academic-over-criticism-about-us-tour_a_23428355/|title=AfriForum Heavyweight Launches Attack On Academic Over Criticism About US Tour|date=6 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref> Following the video posting, du Plessis and her family received threats of violence.<ref name=\"huffPoProfThreatened\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/07/professor-threatened-after-afriforum-criticism-dont-get-too-comfortable-youre-next_a_23429098/|title=Professor Threatened After AfriForum Criticism: 'Don't Get Too Comfortable, You're Next'|date=8 May 2018|publisher= Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ThreatsViolenceHanging\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/varsity-prof-on-afriforums-angry-roets-threat-of-violence-hanging-not-acceptable-20180507|title=Varsity prof on AfriForum's 'angry' Roets: 'Threat of violence, hanging not acceptable'|work=News24|date=2018-05-07}}</ref><ref name=\"habibHitsOutAfriforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/p2-academic-adam-habib-hits-out-at-disgusting-afriforum-leaders-20180510|title=Academic Adam Habib hits out at 'disgusting' AfriForum leaders|publisher=|date=2018-05-10}}</ref> A petition condemning the threats against academics was subsequently circulated.<ref name=\"huffPocademicPetitionCirculated\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2018/05/14/petition-against-afriforum-over-threat-to-academics_a_23434037/|title=Petition Against AfriForum Over Threat To Academics|date=14 May 2018|publisher=Huffington Post South Africa}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, when AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel was asked near the end of a radio interview whether he believed [[Apartheid]] was a [[Crime of apartheid|crime against humanity]], he replied by saying \"I don\u2019t think that apartheid was a crime against humanity, but I think it was wrong.\"<ref name=\"mgMay2018KrielApartheidCrime\">{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-05-14-i-dont-think-apartheid-was-a-crime-against-humanity-afriforums-kallie-kriel|title=I don't think apartheid was a crime against humanity \u2013 Afriforum's Kriel|first=Mashadi|last=Kekana|newspaper=Mail and Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"citizenKrielApartheidCrime\">{{cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/news-cns/1926171/apartheid-was-not-a-crime-afriforum/|title=Apartheid was not a crime \u2013 AfriForum|first=Robinson|last=Nqola|publisher=The Citizen}}</ref><ref name=\"702ApartheidCrimeKriel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.702.co.za/articles/303461/i-dont-think-apartheid-was-a-crime-against-humanity-kriel|title=AfriForum's Kallie Kriel: I don't think apartheid was a crime against humanity|website=702}}</ref><ref name=\"news24ApartheidCrimeKriel\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apartheid-was-not-a-crime-against-humanity-afriforum-ceo-20180514|title=Apartheid was not a crime against humanity - AfriForum CEO|work=News24|date=2018-05-14}}</ref><ref name=\"iolKrielCrimeHumanity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/apartheid-no-crime-against-humanity-says-afriforums-kriel-14973712|title=Apartheid no crime against humanity, says AfriForum's Kriel|publisher=IOL News}}</ref><ref name =\"timesLiveUproarApartheid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-15-uproar-over-remark-that-apartheid-was-not-a-crime-against-humanity-by-afriforum-ceo/|title='Apartheid was not a crime against humanity': AfriForum CEO's remark sparks outrage|publisher=Times Live}}</ref><ref name=\"timesLiveWhoIsKriel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-15-who-is-afriforum-ceo-kallie-kriel/|title=Who is AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel?|publisher=Times Live}}</ref><ref name=\"iolKrielTryingToRevise\">{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/kriel-trying-to-revise-history-14998001|title=Kriel trying to revise history|publisher=Pretoria News}}</ref>. The organisation had previously described Apartheid as a \"so-called historical injustice\"<ref name=\"huffPoFerialMorake\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/ferial-haffajee/ferial-haffajee-tumi-morake-solidarity-and-21st-century-baasskap_a_23216514/|title=Ferial Haffajee: Tumi Morake, Solidarity And 21st Century Baasskap|date=20 September 2017|work=Huffington Post}}</ref><ref name=\"news24DuPreez2016Hijacking\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-05-15-apartheid-not-a-crime-against-humanity--afriforum-ceo/|title=Apartheid not a crime against humanity \u2013 AfriForum CEO|website=SowetanLIVE}}</ref><ref name=\"businessDayApartheidCrime\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2018-05-15-apartheid-not-a-crime-against-humanity--says-afriforum-ceo-kallie-kriel/|title=Apartheid not a crime against humanity, says AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel|publisher=Business Day}}</ref> and its deputy leader Ernst Roets has described Apartheid as a \"wooly concept\".<ref name=\"huffPoParallelState\"/>\n \nIn March 2019, AfriForum released a documentary called ''Disrupted Land'', about land reform and expropriation in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201903130571.html|title=South Africa: 'Verwoerd' Documentary Must be Retracted, Urges IRR, AfriForum Says 'Nee Wat'|first=Pieter Du|last=Toit|date=March 13, 2019|website=allAfrica.com}}</ref> In one clip, an interviewee defends HF Verwoerd's policies.  This led the Institute of Race Relations to accuse Afriforum of \"sanitising the motives behind apartheid and the brutality of its practices\" and of \"soft-soaping the evils of apartheid\".<ref name=\"news24-apartheid-irr-13032019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/verwoerd-documentary-must-retracted-urges-irr-afriforum-says-neewat-20190313|title='Verwoerd' documentary must be retracted, urges IRR, AfriForum says 'nee wat'|date=13 March 2019|work=News24}}</ref><ref name=\"bdlive-vanonselen-13032019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/opinion/columnists/2019-03-13-gareth-van-onselen-afriforums-disgraceful-and-immoral-documentary/|title=GARETH VAN ONSELEN: AfriForum\u2019s disgraceful and immoral documentary|date=13 March 2019|work=News24}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, [[Huffington Post|The Huffington Post SA]] published an editorial with several claims about AfriForum.  The press ombudsman's investigation revealed that the editor had blundered badly by assuming that AfriForum and Solidarity was the same organisation, and that claims and actions that were ascribed to AfriForum did in fact relate entirely to Solidarity.  The ombudsman rejected Huffington Post's editor's reasoning that AfriForum and Solidarity is the same organisation because among others they are both part of the \"Solidarity Movement\" and because their head offices are in the same building.  The press ombudsman ruled that Huffington Post's bungle was a \"serious breach\" of the press code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-huffington-post-sa-4205|title=AfriForum vs. Huffington Post SA|publisher=Press Council|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111524/https://presscouncil.org.za/Ruling/View/afriforum-vs-huffington-post-sa-4205|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tumi Morake: A Victim Of South Africa's 'Bell Pottinger' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/pieter-du-toit/tumi-morake-a-victim-of-south-africas-bell-pottinger_a_23207253/ |website=HuffPost South Africa |language=en |date=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn October 2010, with regard to AfriForum's response to [[Absa Group Limited|Absa Bank]] softening stance on quotas in rugby, Ferial Haffajee wrote in a column in City Press thaty \"while AfriForum is an excellent lobby group with a sense of strategy and tactics, it should be careful that its radical tactics do not dissemble into racist special pleading \u2013 a deeply conservative impulse\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/Columnists/Laager-mentality-is-a-load-of-bull-20101002/ |title=Laager mentality is a load of bull |work=News24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119232400/http://www.citypress.co.za/Columnists/Laager-mentality-is-a-load-of-bull-20101002 |archivedate=2012-11-19 }}</ref>.\n\nIn a column in July 2012, University of Cape Town Professor Pierre de Vos criticised Minister of Higher Education Blade Nzimande's \"blistering attack against the liberal notion of civil society\", and stated that the appropriate way to \"engage with organisations [such as Afriforum] is not to mutter darkly about how they are trying to take over the country by having the cheek to promote their own ideas\" but to \"criticise their ideas and the actions they take and provide arguments for why one\u2019s own ideas are better\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://constitutionallyspeaking.co.za/how-not-to-engage-in-a-battle-of-ideas/|title=How not to engage in a battle of ideas|work=constitutionallyspeaking.co.za}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has been criticized by the ruling ANC but also by many media outlets and academics. \n\nThe survivalist group Kommandokorps criticised Afriforum in February 2012, saying that Afriforum \"had not done much to prevent farm murders\".  This was in response to Afriforum's criticism of Kommandokorps in which Afriforum CEO Kallie Kriel said that Kommandokorps' treatment of young people at training camps is \"immoral and inexcusable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kommandokorps-denies-racism-20120227|title=Kommandokorps denies racism|work=News24|date=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of 2014, the [[Commission for the Promotion and Protection of the Rights of Cultural, Religious and Linguistic Communities]], criticised AfriForum's \"Save Afrikaans schools\" campaign in a press release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.za/speech/DynamicAction?pageid=461&sid=24488&tid=53893 |title=Redirecting old link |work=info.gov.za }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  The campaign followed Gauteng Department of Basic Education's decision to force three Afrikaans-medium schools in Fochville to relinquish their status as Afrikaans-medium schools at the start of the 2012 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/crlrc-meant-to-support-not-oppose-minority-rights-|title=CRLRC meant to support not oppose minority rights - AfriForum - DOCUMENTS &#124; Politicsweb|website=www.politicsweb.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the [[African National Congress Youth League]] stated that AfriForum is \"the defender of white privilege\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/afriforum-defender-of-white-priviledge-ancyl-1.1313072|title=Afriforum 'defender of white privilege': ANCYL|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online}}</ref>, after AfriForum lodged charges of hate speech with the police and the Equality Court against ANCYL deputy president for statements relating to land held by white farmers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-06-06-lamola-hate-speech/|title=Unions to lay hate speech charges against Lamola|website=The M&G Online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/06/Hate-speech-case-opened-against-Lamola|title=Lamola hate speech case opened|first=Stephen|last=Grootes|website=ewn.co.za}}</ref>\n\nIn a newspaper column in May 2018, [[Max du Preez]] described AfriForum's position as \"reactionary identity politics\".  He said that AfriForum \"now totally dominates the socio-political discourse among white Afrikaners\" and that they are \"sanctioned by soft editorials and columns by prominent members of the Afrikaans commentariat\".  He claimed that some Afrikaners who criticised AfriForum were \"aggressively demonised, insulted, belittled and even threatened\".<ref name=\"duPreezAfriForumDaProblem\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/Columnists/MaxduPreez/the-problem-afriforum-is-causing-the-da-20180515|title=The problem AfriForum is causing the DA|work=News24|date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nIn a radio interview in May 2018, vice chancellor of the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] [[Adam Habib]] criticised AfriForum for \"linking up with fascists\" such as the French [[National Front (France)|National Front]], the Italian [[Five Star Movement]], Germany's [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]] and US president Donald Trump's national security adviser John Bolton, whom Habib referred to during the same interview as \"a known fascist\", during Kriel and Roets' 2018 world tour.<ref name=\"iolKrielTryingToRevise\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commonscat|AfriForum}}\n* {{official website|https://www.afriforum.co.za/}} {{in lang|af|en}}\n\n{{Politics of South Africa navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in South Africa]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Civil rights organizations]]\n", "name_user": "KevinL81", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added context to \"Minority Rights\" section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AfriForum"}
{"title_page": "Randwick Racecourse", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox racecourse\n|name         = Randwick Racecourse\n|image        = [[File:Royal Randwick Racecourse.jpg|250px]]\n|caption      = Randwick Racecourse from above\n|website      = http://www.australianturfclub.com.au/\n|location     = [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n|coordinates  = {{coord|33|54|39|S|151|13|49|E|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|owner        = [[Australian Turf Club]]\n|opened       = 1833<ref>[http://www.australianturfclub.com.au/ Randwick Racecourse official website]</ref>\n|track        =\n|closed       =\n|channel      =\n|racetype     =\n|coursetype   =\n|notableraces = [[The Everest]]<br />[[Australian Derby]]<br /> [[Doncaster Handicap]]<br /> [[Queen Elizabeth Stakes (ATC)|Queen Elizabeth Stakes]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse Track.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Randwick Racecourse on Derby Day 2007]]\n[[File:Poitrel 1920 AJC Randwick Plate Trainer Harry Robinson.jpg|thumb|250px|Randwick Racecourse\non Randwick Plate Day 1920]]\n[[File:1952 Randwick Racecourse Sydney Members Stand & Enclosure.jpg|thumb|250px|Members stand and enclosure in 1952.]]\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse, Sydney , 1863 by unknown photographer from The State Library of New South Wales.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Randwick Racecourse in 1863]]\n[[File:1952 Randwick Racecourse Sydney Tramway Exit Bridge.jpg|thumb|250px|The racecourse tramway exit bridge in 1952.]]\n[[File:Randwick racecourse 1920.jpg|thumb|250px|Former 1920 racecourse tram station and southern exit at Ascot Street.]]\n[[File:WYD08 FinalMass.JPG|thumb|250px|The Final Mass for [[World Youth Day 2008]] was held at Randwick Racecourse (dubbed ''Southern Cross Precinct'' specifically for the event) and was attended by 350,000<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/07/20/pope.australia.ap/index.html CNN Reports on WYD08]</ref> people.]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:UNSW and sydney.JPG|thumb|right|300px|The racecourse in relation to Sydney, [[UNSW]] is in the foreground]] -->\n'''Royal Randwick Racecourse''' is a [[racecourse]] for [[horse racing]] located in the [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]] of [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]. Randwick Racecourse is [[Crown Land]]<ref>[http://23.101.218.132/Prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LC20110823015?Open&refNavID=HA8_1 NSW Parliament - AJC & STC Merger Amendment Bill 2011]</ref> leased to the [[Australian Turf Club]] and known to many Sydney racegoers as headquarters. The racecourse is located about six&nbsp;kilometres from the [[Sydney Central Business District]] in the suburb of [[Randwick, New South Wales|Randwick]]. The course proper has a circumference of 2224m with a home straight of 410m.<ref>[http://theraceguide.com.au/tracks/3-royal-randwick Royal Randwick - The Race Guide]</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2017, the inaugural running of [[The Everest]] was held at Royal Randwick. The Everest is the richest race in Australia and the richest turf race in the world with $10 million in prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/21097-2/|title=The Everest, World\u2019s Richest Turf Event|website=www.australianturfclub.com.au|language=en|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, Randwick hosts The Championships, a two-day season-ending meeting in April that offers over AUD$20 million in prize money.<ref>[http://www.thechampionships.com.au/the-event.aspx The Championships]</ref> It features several Group 1 races such as the [[Australian Derby]], [[Doncaster Handicap]] and [[Queen Elizabeth Stakes (ATC)|Queen Elizabeth Stakes]].\n\nOther annual events include the [[Sydney Carnival]], Spring Carnival<ref>[http://www.visitnsw.com/events/sydney-spring-carnival Sydney Spring Carnival - Randwick]</ref> and the Chinese Festival of Racing.<ref>[https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/chinese-festival-of-racing-welcomed-to-royal-randwick/ Chinese Festival of Racing]</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn January 1833, NSW Governor [[Richard Bourke]] designated the land for use as a racecourse. Up until then, [[Hyde Park, Sydney|Hyde Park]] in the [[Sydney]] CBD had been the main venue for racing within the city. The first race held at Randwick was a private event held in June 1833. The course was originally known as the 'Sandy Course' due to the condition of the ground. In 1840 racing ceased at the venue and was only used for training.\n\nIn the early 1840s, the Australian Jockey Club (AJC) was formed and in 1860 moved its headquarters to Randwick. In May of that year, racing resumed at the venue with a crowd of 6,000 people attending.\n\nIn 1863 the land was officially granted to the AJC and was held until 2011 when the AJC and the Sydney Turf Club (STC) merged to become the [[Australian Turf Club]] (ATC). The ATC are the current operators of Royal Randwick Racecourse.<ref>''[http://www2.sl.nsw.gov.au/archive/discover_collections/society_art/races/randwick/ Royal Randwick Racecourse]'' - Archive from the State Library of New South Wales</ref>\n\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse Sydney N.S.W. Champions Beauford, Eurythmic, Cetigne, Poitrel and Gloaming 1918 - 1922.jpg|thumb|centre|1000px|upright|Champions of the Past 1915 - 1925]]\n\n==='Royal' Randwick===\nOn 22 February 1992, Queen Elizabeth II visited Randwick Racecourse<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/02/18/Queen-Elizabeth-Prince-Philip-arrive-in-Australia/4987698389200/ Queen Elizabeth, Prince Philip arrive in Australia ]</ref> and opened the Paddock Stand. On this date, upon request, the Queen granted permission for the venue to be known as Royal Randwick. From this date the venue was officially able to be referred to as 'Royal Randwick'. An extract from a letter from [[Kenneth Scott (courtier)|Kenneth Scott]], Deputy Private Secretary to Queen Elizabeth II, to the club reads: \"You do not need me to tell you how much The Queen and The Duke of Edinburgh enjoyed their visit to the Royal Randwick Racecourse today. Her Majesty was particularly glad that she was able, on this occasion, to legitimise your traditional title of \"Royal\" and to open a very handsome new Grandstand.\"\n\n== Races ==\nThe following is a list of [[Group races]] which are contested at Randwick Racecourse.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-       \n|'''Grp'''\n|'''Race Name'''\n|'''Age'''\n|'''Sex'''\n|'''Weight'''\n|'''Distance'''\n|'''Date'''\n|-\n|1\n|[[Australian Derby]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Queen Elizabeth Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Sydney Cup]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|3200\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[All Aged Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Canterbury Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1300\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Doncaster Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Champagne Stakes (Australia)|Champagne Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Sires Produce Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Oaks]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|2400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Winx Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|August\n|-\n|1\n|[[Epsom Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|October\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Metropolitan Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|October\n|-\n<!--|1\n|[[The Everest]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|October\n|- -->\n|1\n|[[Flight Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1600\n|October\n|-\n\n|1\n|[[George Main Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|September\n|-\n|1\n|[[Queen Of The Turf Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|F&M\n|qlty\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Surround Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1400\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Randwick Guineas]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1600\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Spring Champion Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2000\n|October\n|-\n|1\n|[[T J Smith Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Chipping Norton Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Apollo Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[AJC Chairmans Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2600\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Breeders' Classic]]\n|4YO+\n|Mares\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Challenge Stakes (ATC)|Challenge Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1000\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Chelmsford Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Emancipation Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|F&M\n|sw+p\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Hill Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1900\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Furious Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Tramway Quality Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Light Fingers Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw+p\n|1100\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Roman Consul Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1200\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Royal Sovereign Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|C&G\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Skyline Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|C&G\n|sw\n|1200\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Sweet Embrace Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1200\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Sapphire Stakes (Australia)|Sapphire Stakes]]\n|Open\n|F&M\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Premiere Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[The Shorts (ATC)|The Shorts]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|sw+p\n|1100\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Villiers Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|December\n|-\n|3\n|[[Adrian Knox Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|qlty\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|3\n|[[Bill Ritchie Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|3\n|[[Colin Stephen Quality Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|September\n|-\n|3\n|[[Craven Plate]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|2000\n|October\n|-\n|3\n|[[Breeders' Plate]]\n|2YO\n|C&G\n|sw\n|1000\n|October\n|-\n|3\n|[[Frank Packer Plate]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|3\n|[[Southern Cross Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|3\n|[[Kindergarten Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1100\n|March\n|-\n|3\n|[[Liverpool City Cup]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1300\n|March\n|-\n|3\n|[[Summer Cup (horse racing)|Summer Cup]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|December\n|-\n|L\n|[[Randwick City Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2000\n|March\n|-\n|}\n\n== Venue ==\nBesides horseracing, Randwick Racecourse has been used as a venue for many other events including [[concert]]s and religious [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]]es.\n\nIn 1970, [[Pope Paul VI]] celebrated [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] at Randwick<ref>Search under Manuscripts and Pictures on [http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/ New South Wales library] for \"Australian tour of Pope Paul VI Randwick\"</ref> as part of his pastoral visit to Australia. The Racecourse  was also the site of a [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] held by [[Pope John Paul II]] in 1995 for the [[Beatification]] ceremony of Australia's first potential saint [[Mary MacKillop]]. It was also the site of the vigil and final mass of [[World Youth Day 2008]] in July 2008.  Racing was stopped for several weeks, due to the alterations needed to hold over 400,000 people. This move had been opposed by the Randwick Trainers Association, which holds lease interests over some areas intended to be used for the event.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2007/10/04/1191091276220.html Back off, irate horse trainers warn Pell]</ref> The dispute was resolved,<ref>''[http://www.ajc.com.au/mediaandnews/newsarticle.aspx?ID=148 World Youth Day reaches agreement with racing industry]'' - Article on Australian Jockey Club website</ref> by the [[Government of Australia|federal government]] and the [[Government of New South Wales|state government]] jointly pledging $40 million as reimbursement to the racing industry.<ref>''[http://au.news.yahoo.com/071115/2/14xhu.html Racing industry offered payout for Pope] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20071204033135/http://au.news.yahoo.com/071115/2/14xhu.html |date=4 December 2007 }}'' - Article on au.news.yahoo.com</ref> The famous racecourse has also appeared in several films, including ''[[Mission: Impossible 2]]''.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/search/title?locations=Royal%20Randwick%20Racecourse,%20Sydney,%20New%20South%20Wales,%20Australia&ref_=ttloc_loc_13 IMDb: Movies Filmed at Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\nRandwick Racecourse is also used as an exam venue by the [[University of New South Wales]].\n\nIn addition, the annual [[Future Music Festival]] was held at the racecourse from 2006<ref>\"[http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/musicnews/s4107581.htm Future music festival announces 2015 dates]\" - Article on ABC Website</ref> until it was cancelled in 2015<ref>\"[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/future-music-festival-is-over-it-will-not-return-in-2016-says-mushroom-group-20150402-1mdkfq.html Future Music Festival is Over]\" - Article on smh.com.au</ref>\n\n===Buildings & Spaces===\n====Queen Elizabeth II Grandstand: 2013 - Present====\nThe [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] (QEII) Grandstand is the main [[grandstand]] building. Originally constructed in 1969, it was torn down to its bare structure and rebuilt into the current state in 2012 and reopened to the public in 2013. It is 110m in length and 6 storeys high.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Official / Members Stand: 1886 - Present====\nThe Official / Members Stand was constructed in 1886 and still remains today although it has been extended and modified multiple times, in 1907, 1914 and 1920.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Theatre of the Horse (ToTH): 2013 - Present====\nThe Theatre of the Horse, also known as the \"ToTH\", is an outdoor auditorium for the presentation of thoroughbred racehorses both before and after a race. The ToTH is linked to the track-front via a tunnel in which the horses access the track. The ToTH has a capacity of 4,500 and is also used for live music events and functions. The construction of the ToTH was not without controversy, many racegoers have criticised the space for not being located trackside.\n\n====Saddling Paddock Tote Building: 1917 - Present====\nThe Saddling Paddock Tote Building, known as the Octagonal bar, is located behind the main grandstand. It was initially constructed in 1917 to house a [[Tote Board|Totalisator]], the fourth in the world to be installed. The building is now used as an event space and a bar on race days.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Owners Pavilion: 2013 - Present====\nThe Owners Pavilion is located directly adjacent to the Theatre of the Hose and is a private space for racehorse owners. The pavilion was constructed at the same time as the new QEII Grandstand and ToTH.<ref>[https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/royal-randwick/owners-pavilion/ Australian Turf Club: Owners Pavilion]</ref>\n\n====Paddock Stand: 1992 - 2012====\nThe Paddock Stand replaced the St Ledger Stand and Grandstand and was a two-storey, long, horizontal structure. The stand was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II in February 1992, it was also on this occasion that the Queen certified Randwick as \"Royal\". The Paddock Stand was demolished in 2012 to make way for the new QEII Grandstand.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Tea House: 1914 - 2012====\nThe Tea House was a large structure at 50m long, 27m wide and two storeys high and could accommodate 1,000 racegoers. The original Tea house burnt down in 1917 and was immediately reconstructed to the same specifications.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/storm-in-a-tea-house-as-randwick-ignores-past-20111026-1mk36.html Article on SMH: Storm in a Tea House as Randwick ignores past]</ref> The Tea House was demolished in 2012 as part of the upgrades to the current layout.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Ladies Stand: 1910 - 1998====\nThe Ladies Stand, also known as the Queens or Royal Stand was constructed in 1910<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref> and remained until 1998.\n\n====First Grandstand: 1860 - 1875====\nThe First Grandstand was constructed for the first race meeting at Randwick and was made of American timber. Designed by John Hilly, it was intended to be temporary but stood for 15 years.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Second Grandstand: 1876 - 1988====\nThe Second Grandstand, also known as the Paddock Stand, was constructed to replace the initial grandstand constructed on site. It was extended in 1907 and 1914 and remained for more than 100 years to 1988 when it was demolished to make way for the new Paddock Stand.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SAM_0673.jpg|Royal Randwick, Grandstand at left\nFile:SAM_0703.jpg|The [[teahouse|Tea House]]\nFile:SAM_0708.jpg|Tea House and Rose Garden\nFile:SAM_0702.jpg|Skyline and Tea House viewed from Grandstand\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Horses|Sports}}}}\n* [[List of Australian organisations with royal patronage]]\n* [[Big Stable Newmarket]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page5102339 Randwick Racecourse, ''Australian Town and Country Journal'', (Saturday, 25 September 1886), p.661;] [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71067921 ''Australian Town and Country Journal'', (Saturday, 25 September 1886), p.654.]\n* {{cite web | url = http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/randwick_racecourse | title = Randwick Racecourse | accessdate = 29 September 2015 | author = Mark Dunn | date = 2008 | work=[[Dictionary of Sydney]]}} <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Creative Commons license|CC-By-SA]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n\n{{SydneyRacing}}\n{{Sydney landmarks}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category| Randwick racecourse }}\n*[http://www.australianturfclub.com.au Australian Turf Club]\n\n[[Category:Horse racing venues in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Randwick Racecourse]]\n[[Category:1833 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1833]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox racecourse\n|name         = Randwick Racecourse\n|image        = [[File:Royal Randwick Racecourse.jpg|250px]]\n|caption      = Randwick Racecourse from above\n|website      = http://www.australianturfclub.com.au/\n|location     = [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n|coordinates  = {{coord|33|54|39|S|151|13|49|E|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|owner        = [[Australian Turf Club]]\n|opened       = 1833<ref>[http://www.australianturfclub.com.au/ Randwick Racecourse official website]</ref>\n|track        =\n|closed       =\n|channel      =\n|racetype     =\n|coursetype   =\n|notableraces = [[The Everest]]<br />[[Australian Derby]]<br /> [[Doncaster Handicap]]<br /> [[Queen Elizabeth Stakes (ATC)|Queen Elizabeth Stakes]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse Track.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Randwick Racecourse on Derby Day 2007]]\n[[File:Poitrel 1920 AJC Randwick Plate Trainer Harry Robinson.jpg|thumb|250px|Randwick Racecourse\non Randwick Plate Day 1920]]\n[[File:1952 Randwick Racecourse Sydney Members Stand & Enclosure.jpg|thumb|250px|Members stand and enclosure in 1952.]]\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse, Sydney , 1863 by unknown photographer from The State Library of New South Wales.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Randwick Racecourse in 1863]]\n[[File:1952 Randwick Racecourse Sydney Tramway Exit Bridge.jpg|thumb|250px|The racecourse tramway exit bridge in 1952.]]\n[[File:Randwick racecourse 1920.jpg|thumb|250px|Former 1920 racecourse tram station and southern exit at Ascot Street.]]\n[[File:WYD08 FinalMass.JPG|thumb|250px|The Final Mass for [[World Youth Day 2008]] was held at Randwick Racecourse (dubbed ''Southern Cross Precinct'' specifically for the event) and was attended by 350,000<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/07/20/pope.australia.ap/index.html CNN Reports on WYD08]</ref> people.]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:UNSW and sydney.JPG|thumb|right|300px|The racecourse in relation to Sydney, [[UNSW]] is in the foreground]] -->\n'''Royal Randwick Racecourse''' is a [[racecourse]] for [[horse racing]] located in the [[Eastern Suburbs (Sydney)|Eastern Suburbs]] of [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]. Randwick Racecourse is [[Crown Land]]<ref>[http://23.101.218.132/Prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LC20110823015?Open&refNavID=HA8_1 NSW Parliament - AJC & STC Merger Amendment Bill 2011]</ref> leased to the [[Australian Turf Club]] and known to many Sydney racegoers as headquarters. The racecourse is located about six&nbsp;kilometres from the [[Sydney Central Business District]] in the suburb of [[Randwick, New South Wales|Randwick]]. The course proper has a circumference of 2224m with a home straight of 410m.<ref>[http://theraceguide.com.au/tracks/3-royal-randwick Royal Randwick - The Race Guide]</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2017, the inaugural running of [[The Everest]] was held at Royal Randwick. The Everest is the richest race in Australia and the richest turf race in the world with $10 million in prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/21097-2/|title=The Everest, World\u2019s Richest Turf Event|website=www.australianturfclub.com.au|language=en|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, Randwick hosts The Championships, a two-day season-ending meeting in April that offers over AUD$20 million in prize money.<ref>[http://www.thechampionships.com.au/the-event.aspx The Championships]</ref> It features several Group 1 races such as the [[Australian Derby]], [[Doncaster Handicap]] and [[Queen Elizabeth Stakes (ATC)|Queen Elizabeth Stakes]].\n\nOther annual events include the [[Sydney Carnival]], Spring Carnival<ref>[http://www.visitnsw.com/events/sydney-spring-carnival Sydney Spring Carnival - Randwick]</ref> and the Chinese Festival of Racing.<ref>[https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/chinese-festival-of-racing-welcomed-to-royal-randwick/ Chinese Festival of Racing]</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn January 1833, NSW Governor [[Richard Bourke]] designated the land for use as a racecourse. Up until then, [[Hyde Park, Sydney|Hyde Park]] in the [[Sydney]] CBD had been the main venue for racing within the city. The first race held at Randwick was a private event held in June 1833. The course was originally known as the 'Sandy Course' due to the condition of the ground. In 1840 racing ceased at the venue and was only used for training.\n\nIn the early 1840s, the Australian Jockey Club (AJC) was formed and in 1860 moved its headquarters to Randwick. In May of that year, racing resumed at the venue with a crowd of 6,000 people attending.\n\nIn 1863 the land was officially granted to the AJC and was held until 2011 when the AJC and the Sydney Turf Club (STC) merged to become the [[Australian Turf Club]] (ATC). The ATC are the current operators of Royal Randwick Racecourse.<ref>''[http://www2.sl.nsw.gov.au/archive/discover_collections/society_art/races/randwick/ Royal Randwick Racecourse]'' - Archive from the State Library of New South Wales</ref>\n\n[[File:Randwick Racecourse Sydney N.S.W. Champions Beauford, Eurythmic, Cetigne, Poitrel and Gloaming 1918 - 1922.jpg|thumb|centre|1000px|upright|Champions of the Past 1915 - 1925]]\n\n==='Royal' Randwick===\nOn 22 February 1992, Queen Elizabeth II visited Randwick Racecourse<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/02/18/Queen-Elizabeth-Prince-Philip-arrive-in-Australia/4987698389200/ Queen Elizabeth, Prince Philip arrive in Australia ]</ref> and opened the Paddock Stand. On this date, upon request, the Queen granted permission for the venue to be known as Royal Randwick. From this date the venue was officially able to be referred to as 'Royal Randwick'. An extract from a letter from [[Kenneth Scott (courtier)|Kenneth Scott]], Deputy Private Secretary to Queen Elizabeth II, to the club reads: \"You do not need me to tell you how much The Queen and The Duke of Edinburgh enjoyed their visit to the Royal Randwick Racecourse today. Her Majesty was particularly glad that she was able, on this occasion, to legitimise your traditional title of \"Royal\" and to open a very handsome new Grandstand.\"\n\n== Races ==\nThe following is a list of [[Group races]] which are contested at Randwick Racecourse.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-       \n|'''Grp'''\n|'''Race Name'''\n|'''Age'''\n|'''Sex'''\n|'''Weight'''\n|'''Distance'''\n|'''Date'''\n|-\n|1\n|[[Australian Derby]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Queen Elizabeth Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Sydney Cup]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|3200\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[All Aged Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Canterbury Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1300\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Doncaster Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Champagne Stakes (Australia)|Champagne Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Sires Produce Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Oaks]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|2400\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Winx Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|August\n|-\n|1\n|[[Epsom Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|October\n|-\n|1\n|[[AJC Metropolitan Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|October\n|-\n<!--|1\n|[[The Everest]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|October\n|- -->\n|1\n|[[Flight Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1600\n|October\n|-\n|3\n|[[Breeders' Plate]]\n|2YO\n|C&G\n|sw\n|1000\n|October\n|-\n|1\n|[[George Main Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|September\n|-\n|1\n|[[Queen Of The Turf Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|F&M\n|qlty\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Surround Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1400\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Randwick Guineas]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1600\n|March\n|-\n|1\n|[[Spring Champion Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2000\n|October\n|-\n|1\n|[[T J Smith Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|April\n|-\n|1\n|[[Chipping Norton Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Apollo Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1400\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[AJC Chairmans Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2600\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Breeders' Classic]]\n|4YO+\n|Mares\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Challenge Stakes (ATC)|Challenge Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1000\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Chelmsford Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1600\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Emancipation Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|F&M\n|sw+p\n|1600\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Hill Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1900\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Furious Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Tramway Quality Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Light Fingers Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|sw+p\n|1100\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Roman Consul Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1200\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Royal Sovereign Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|C&G\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|2\n|[[Skyline Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|C&G\n|sw\n|1200\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Sweet Embrace Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Fillies\n|sw\n|1200\n|March\n|-\n|2\n|[[Sapphire Stakes (Australia)|Sapphire Stakes]]\n|Open\n|F&M\n|sw+p\n|1200\n|April\n|-\n|2\n|[[Premiere Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|wfa\n|1200\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[The Shorts (ATC)|The Shorts]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|sw+p\n|1100\n|September\n|-\n|2\n|[[Villiers Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1600\n|December\n|-\n|3\n|[[Adrian Knox Stakes]]\n|3YO\n|Fillies\n|qlty\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|3\n|[[Bill Ritchie Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1400\n|September\n|-\n|3\n|[[Colin Stephen Quality Handicap]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|September\n|-\n|3\n|[[Craven Plate]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|wfa\n|2000\n|October\n|-\n|3\n|[[Frank Packer Plate]]\n|3YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|2000\n|April\n|-\n|3\n|[[Southern Cross Stakes]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1200\n|February\n|-\n|3\n|[[Kindergarten Stakes]]\n|2YO\n|Open\n|sw\n|1100\n|March\n|-\n|3\n|[[Liverpool City Cup]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|hcp\n|1300\n|March\n|-\n|3\n|[[Summer Cup (horse racing)|Summer Cup]]\n|Open\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2400\n|December\n|-\n|L\n|[[Randwick City Stakes]]\n|3YO+\n|Open\n|hcp\n|2000\n|March\n|-\n|}\n\n== Venue ==\nBesides horseracing, Randwick Racecourse has been used as a venue for many other events including [[concert]]s and religious [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]]es.\n\nIn 1970, [[Pope Paul VI]] celebrated [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] at Randwick<ref>Search under Manuscripts and Pictures on [http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/ New South Wales library] for \"Australian tour of Pope Paul VI Randwick\"</ref> as part of his pastoral visit to Australia. The Racecourse  was also the site of a [[Mass (liturgy)|mass]] held by [[Pope John Paul II]] in 1995 for the [[Beatification]] ceremony of Australia's first potential saint [[Mary MacKillop]]. It was also the site of the vigil and final mass of [[World Youth Day 2008]] in July 2008.  Racing was stopped for several weeks, due to the alterations needed to hold over 400,000 people. This move had been opposed by the Randwick Trainers Association, which holds lease interests over some areas intended to be used for the event.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2007/10/04/1191091276220.html Back off, irate horse trainers warn Pell]</ref> The dispute was resolved,<ref>''[http://www.ajc.com.au/mediaandnews/newsarticle.aspx?ID=148 World Youth Day reaches agreement with racing industry]'' - Article on Australian Jockey Club website</ref> by the [[Government of Australia|federal government]] and the [[Government of New South Wales|state government]] jointly pledging $40 million as reimbursement to the racing industry.<ref>''[http://au.news.yahoo.com/071115/2/14xhu.html Racing industry offered payout for Pope] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20071204033135/http://au.news.yahoo.com/071115/2/14xhu.html |date=4 December 2007 }}'' - Article on au.news.yahoo.com</ref> The famous racecourse has also appeared in several films, including ''[[Mission: Impossible 2]]''.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/search/title?locations=Royal%20Randwick%20Racecourse,%20Sydney,%20New%20South%20Wales,%20Australia&ref_=ttloc_loc_13 IMDb: Movies Filmed at Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\nRandwick Racecourse is also used as an exam venue by the [[University of New South Wales]].\n\nIn addition, the annual [[Future Music Festival]] was held at the racecourse from 2006<ref>\"[http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/musicnews/s4107581.htm Future music festival announces 2015 dates]\" - Article on ABC Website</ref> until it was cancelled in 2015<ref>\"[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/future-music-festival-is-over-it-will-not-return-in-2016-says-mushroom-group-20150402-1mdkfq.html Future Music Festival is Over]\" - Article on smh.com.au</ref>\n\n===Buildings & Spaces===\n====Queen Elizabeth II Grandstand: 2013 - Present====\nThe [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] (QEII) Grandstand is the main [[grandstand]] building. Originally constructed in 1969, it was torn down to its bare structure and rebuilt into the current state in 2012 and reopened to the public in 2013. It is 110m in length and 6 storeys high.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Official / Members Stand: 1886 - Present====\nThe Official / Members Stand was constructed in 1886 and still remains today although it has been extended and modified multiple times, in 1907, 1914 and 1920.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Theatre of the Horse (ToTH): 2013 - Present====\nThe Theatre of the Horse, also known as the \"ToTH\", is an outdoor auditorium for the presentation of thoroughbred racehorses both before and after a race. The ToTH is linked to the track-front via a tunnel in which the horses access the track. The ToTH has a capacity of 4,500 and is also used for live music events and functions. The construction of the ToTH was not without controversy, many racegoers have criticised the space for not being located trackside.\n\n====Saddling Paddock Tote Building: 1917 - Present====\nThe Saddling Paddock Tote Building, known as the Octagonal bar, is located behind the main grandstand. It was initially constructed in 1917 to house a [[Tote Board|Totalisator]], the fourth in the world to be installed. The building is now used as an event space and a bar on race days.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Owners Pavilion: 2013 - Present====\nThe Owners Pavilion is located directly adjacent to the Theatre of the Hose and is a private space for racehorse owners. The pavilion was constructed at the same time as the new QEII Grandstand and ToTH.<ref>[https://www.australianturfclub.com.au/royal-randwick/owners-pavilion/ Australian Turf Club: Owners Pavilion]</ref>\n\n====Paddock Stand: 1992 - 2012====\nThe Paddock Stand replaced the St Ledger Stand and Grandstand and was a two-storey, long, horizontal structure. The stand was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II in February 1992, it was also on this occasion that the Queen certified Randwick as \"Royal\". The Paddock Stand was demolished in 2012 to make way for the new QEII Grandstand.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Tea House: 1914 - 2012====\nThe Tea House was a large structure at 50m long, 27m wide and two storeys high and could accommodate 1,000 racegoers. The original Tea house burnt down in 1917 and was immediately reconstructed to the same specifications.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/storm-in-a-tea-house-as-randwick-ignores-past-20111026-1mk36.html Article on SMH: Storm in a Tea House as Randwick ignores past]</ref> The Tea House was demolished in 2012 as part of the upgrades to the current layout.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Ladies Stand: 1910 - 1998====\nThe Ladies Stand, also known as the Queens or Royal Stand was constructed in 1910<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref> and remained until 1998.\n\n====First Grandstand: 1860 - 1875====\nThe First Grandstand was constructed for the first race meeting at Randwick and was made of American timber. Designed by John Hilly, it was intended to be temporary but stood for 15 years.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n====Second Grandstand: 1876 - 1988====\nThe Second Grandstand, also known as the Paddock Stand, was constructed to replace the initial grandstand constructed on site. It was extended in 1907 and 1914 and remained for more than 100 years to 1988 when it was demolished to make way for the new Paddock Stand.<ref>[https://www.thoroughbredracing.com/articles/racecourse-architecture-royal-randwick/ Racecourse Architecture: Royal Randwick]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SAM_0673.jpg|Royal Randwick, Grandstand at left\nFile:SAM_0703.jpg|The [[teahouse|Tea House]]\nFile:SAM_0708.jpg|Tea House and Rose Garden\nFile:SAM_0702.jpg|Skyline and Tea House viewed from Grandstand\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Horses|Sports}}}}\n* [[List of Australian organisations with royal patronage]]\n* [[Big Stable Newmarket]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page5102339 Randwick Racecourse, ''Australian Town and Country Journal'', (Saturday, 25 September 1886), p.661;] [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71067921 ''Australian Town and Country Journal'', (Saturday, 25 September 1886), p.654.]\n* {{cite web | url = http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/randwick_racecourse | title = Randwick Racecourse | accessdate = 29 September 2015 | author = Mark Dunn | date = 2008 | work=[[Dictionary of Sydney]]}} <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Creative Commons license|CC-By-SA]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>\n\n{{SydneyRacing}}\n{{Sydney landmarks}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category| Randwick racecourse }}\n*[http://www.australianturfclub.com.au Australian Turf Club]\n\n[[Category:Horse racing venues in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Randwick Racecourse]]\n[[Category:1833 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1833]]\n", "name_user": "LESHAIGH", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reposition Breeders Plate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randwick_Racecourse"}
{"title_page": "No Way Jose (wrestler)", "text_new": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the 15th of April it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that No Way Jose was released along with various other superstars and backstage talent.\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the 15th of April it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that No Way Jose was released as well as various other superstars.\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "name_user": "Chameleon.", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected grammar.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_Way_Jose_(wrestler)"}
{"title_page": "Joan Graves", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n'''Joan Eldridge Graves''' (born 1941/1942)<ref name = THR>{{cite news|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lessons-30-years-movie-ratings-angry-phone-calls-1213531|title = Lessons From 30 Years of Movie Ratings and Angry Phone Calls|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last1 = McClintock|first1 = Pamela|last2 = Noble|first2 = Alexandra|date = May 25, 2019|accessdate = April 15, 2020}}</ref> is an American media professional who served as a senior vice president [[Motion Picture Association of America]] and chair of its [[Classification and Ratings Administration]].<ref name=LA>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/08/business/la-fi-ct-facetime8-2010apr08 |title=The MPAA's Joan Graves watches out for the movie watchers |author=Richard Verrier |date=April 8, 2010 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref>  \n\nGraves studied political science at [[Stanford University]] and worked as a real estate agent.<ref name = OurPeople>{{cite web|url=https://www.mpaa.org/who-we-are/our-people/|title = Our People|website = Motion Picture Association of America|accessdate = July 31, 2018}}</ref> She was recommended for a position on the ratings board in 1988, and was appointed to lead the administration in 2000 by [[Jack Valenti]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Discretion Adviser |url=http://www.stanfordalumni.org/news/magazine/2008/julaug/show/graves.html |publisher=Stanford Magazine |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |date=August 2008 |author=Sonja Bolle}}</ref> In that capacity, she personally hired all the other members of the ratings administration, and was the only one whose identity was disclosed to the public.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://kidstvmovies.about.com/od/mpaa/a/Joan-Graves-Interview-On-The-Mpaa-Movie-Rating-Process.htm | title=Joan Graves Interview on the MPAA Movie Rating Process | work=[[About.com]] | accessdate=May 15, 2014 | author=Bryson, Carey}}</ref> Graves held the position until retiring in May 2019.<ref name = THR/> Graves has defended the Administration's rating system against critics who accuse it of being too lenient toward violence, saying that when the MPAA surveys parents, \"What we find with the violence category is that they think they're getting correct information from us.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/01/07/dont-expect-a-new-movie-ratings-system-in-2014 | title=Don\u2019t Expect Any Major Changes to the MPAA Ratings System in 2014 | work=[[US News]] | date=January 7, 2014 | accessdate=May 15, 2014 | author=Sneed, Tierney}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2502450}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graves, Joan}}\n[[Category:1940s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Motion Picture Association of America people]]\n[[Category:Media people from California]]\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n'''Joan Eldridge Graves''' (born 1941/1942)<ref name = THR>{{cite news|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lessons-30-years-movie-ratings-angry-phone-calls-1213531|title = Lessons From 30 Years of Movie Ratings and Angry Phone Calls|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last1 = McClintock|first1 = Pamela|last2 = Noble|first2 = Alexandra|date = May 25, 2019|accessdate = April 15, 2020}}</ref> G is an American media professional who served as a senior vice president [[Motion Picture Association of America]] and chair of its [[Classification and Ratings Administration]].<ref name=LA>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/08/business/la-fi-ct-facetime8-2010apr08 |title=The MPAA's Joan Graves watches out for the movie watchers |author=Richard Verrier |date=April 8, 2010 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref>  \n\nGraves studied political science at [[Stanford University]] and worked as a real estate agent.<ref name = OurPeople>{{cite web|url=https://www.mpaa.org/who-we-are/our-people/|title = Our People|website = Motion Picture Association of America|accessdate = July 31, 2018}}</ref> She was recommended for a position on the ratings board in 1988, and was appointed to lead the administration in 2000 by [[Jack Valenti]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Discretion Adviser |url=http://www.stanfordalumni.org/news/magazine/2008/julaug/show/graves.html |publisher=Stanford Magazine |accessdate=March 29, 2012 |date=August 2008 |author=Sonja Bolle}}</ref> In that capacity, she personally hired all the other members of the ratings administration, and was the only one whose identity was disclosed to the public.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://kidstvmovies.about.com/od/mpaa/a/Joan-Graves-Interview-On-The-Mpaa-Movie-Rating-Process.htm | title=Joan Graves Interview on the MPAA Movie Rating Process | work=[[About.com]] | accessdate=May 15, 2014 | author=Bryson, Carey}}</ref> Graves held the position until retiring in May 2019.<ref name = THR/> Graves has defended the Administration's rating system against critics who accuse it of being too lenient toward violence, saying that when the MPAA surveys parents, \"What we find with the violence category is that they think they're getting correct information from us.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/01/07/dont-expect-a-new-movie-ratings-system-in-2014 | title=Don\u2019t Expect Any Major Changes to the MPAA Ratings System in 2014 | work=[[US News]] | date=January 7, 2014 | accessdate=May 15, 2014 | author=Sneed, Tierney}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2502450}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graves, Joan}}\n[[Category:1940s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Motion Picture Association of America people]]\n[[Category:Media people from California]]\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sunshineisles2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joan_Graves"}
{"title_page": "Adam Alsing", "text_new": "{{recent death}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adam Alsing\n| image              = Adam Alsing 2015-09-17 001.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Alsing in 2015\n| birth_name         = Rolf Adam Engelbrekt Alsing\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=y|1968|10|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|15|1968|10|12|df=yes}}\n| '''Death Cause'''  = Coronavirus (Covid-19)\n| death_place        = [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]\n| nationality        = Sweden\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Radio and television host\n| years_active       = 1990\u20132020\n| known_for          = ''[[Big Brother (Swedish TV series)|Big Brother]]'', ''[[Adam Live]]'', [[Mix Megapol]]\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n{{short description|Swedish television and radio host|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n\n'''Rolf Adam Engelbrekt Alsing''' (12 October 1968 \u2013 15 April 2020) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[television]] and radio presenter, best known for hosting ''[[Big Brother (Swedish TV series)|Big Brother Sweden]]'' on [[Kanal 5 (Swedish TV channel)|Kanal 5]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0022528/bio|title=Adam Alsing|website=IMDb|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306072844/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0022528/bio|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently he moved to [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] in 2005, hosting the Swedish version of ''[[Jeopardy!]]''. He also presented his own show ''[[Adam Live]]''. He later ventured into radio presenting shows on Rix FM and Mix Megapol.\n\n==Biography==\nAlsing grew up in [[Karlstad]] in [[V\u00e4rmland]] and [[Sollefte\u00e5]] in [[\u00c5ngermanland]]. <ref name=\"vf110902\">{{cite web|title=\u201dMan f\u00e5r s\u00e4llan en s\u00e5n h\u00e4r chans\u201d|url=https://www.vf.se/uncategorized/man-far-sallan-en-san-har-chans/|last=Olsson|first=Martin|publisher=[[V\u00e4rmlands Folkblad]]|date=2 September 2011|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=svenska|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028042736/https://www.vf.se/uncategorized/man-far-sallan-en-san-har-chans/|archive-date=28 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He worked as a disc jockey during his high school years in Karlstad.<ref name=\"Josve1\">{{cite web|title=Adam och Kompani - podcast |url=http://www.tv3.se/adamochkompani|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116053323/http://www.tv3.se/adamochkompani|archivedate=2013-01-16|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> He started hes career as a presenter for several shows on the [[Sveriges Radio]] local broadcasts from V\u00e4rmland at the time called Radio V\u00e4rmland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=93&artikel=7453086|title=JUST NU: V\u00e4rml\u00e4nningen Adam Alsing har g\u00e5tt  bort|first=Marie|last=Hansson|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Sveriges Radio}}</ref>\n\nWhen TV4 started its broadcasts in 1990 he applied for television presenter work, and debuted as presenter for \"Twist & Shout\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv4gruppen.se/Templates/TV4Gruppen/Pages/StandardPage.aspx?id=6121&epslanguage=sv |title=Adam Alsing i Twist & Shout|access-date=2020-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160607214543/http://www.tv4gruppen.se/Templates/TV4Gruppen/Pages/StandardPage.aspx?id=6121&epslanguage=sv |archive-date=2016-06-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1991, he became the presenter of the dating show \"Tur i k\u00e4rlek\" along with [[Agneta Sj\u00f6din]], and presented over 100 episodes of the show.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/Xg7Ajb|title=Adam Alsings liv i bilder \u2013 fr\u00e5n \u201dTur i k\u00e4rlek\u201d till \u201dK\u00e4ndishoppet\u201d|website=Aftonbladet|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In 1993, he moved to [[TV3 (Sweden)|TV3]] and started presenting his own talk show called \"Adam\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> In the mid 1990s, Alsing along with Nikola S\u00f6derlund started the production company \"Think Big Productions\", they produced the shows Utmanarna on TV3, and M\u00e5ndagsklubben on [[Kanal 5 (Swedish TV channel)|Kanal 5]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gaffa.se/nyhet/142854/adam-alsing-aer-doed|title=Adam Alsing \u00e4r d\u00f6d|website=gaffa.se|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlsing presented [[Big Brother Sweden|Big Brother]] between 2000 and 2005 on Kanal 5, as well as the reality series Masterplan in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Alsing ska leda nya dokus\u00e5pan \"Masterplan\"|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/dokusapa/article10383935.ab|last=Bj\u00f6rk|first=Corinna|publisher=[[Aftonbladet]]|date=1 August 2003|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=svenska|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102131944/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/dokusapa/article10383935.ab|archive-date=2 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 2006 and 2007, he presented [[Jeopardy]] on TV4 taking over for [[Magnus H\u00e4renstam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/alsing-var-en-av-vara-stora-lattunderhallare|title=Alsing var en av v\u00e5ra stora l\u00e4ttunderh\u00e5llare|first=Andres|last=Lokko|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Svenska Dagbladet}}</ref> Between 2009 and 2011, he presented ''Sveriges v\u00e4rsta bilf\u00f6rare'' on TV4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/50g43z|title=I tv fick Adam Alsing allt f\u00f6r s\u00e4llan utlopp f\u00f6r sin stora beg\u00e5vning|website=Aftonbladet|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 5 September 2011 and 5 April 2012 Adam Alsing presented \"[[Adam Live]]\", a live talkshow on TV3, and in 2014 he presented Big Brother again this time on [[Kanal 9]].<ref>[http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/article13224970.ab Adam Alsing blir Sveriges Letterman] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033335/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/article13224970.ab |date=2017-08-20}} Aftonbladet Retrieved 15 April 2020</ref> Alsing participated as a contestant in [[P\u00e5 sp\u00e5ret]] in 2011 along with [[Stefan Holm]], the show is broadcast on [[SVT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-var-en-av-nojesvarldens-storsta/|title=Adam Alsing var en av n\u00f6jesv\u00e4rldens st\u00f6rsta|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=93&artikel=4072314|title=Holm och Alsing i \"P\u00e5 sp\u00e5ret\"|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Sveriges Radio}}</ref>\n \n=== Radio ===\nBetween 2004 and 2011, Alsing along with [[Gry Forssell]] and [[Anders Timell]] presented the radio show \u00c4ntligen morgon on Mix Megapol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-lamnar-antligen-morgon/|title=Adam Alsing l\u00e4mnar \"\u00c4ntligen morgon\"|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114211/http://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-lamnar-antligen-morgon/|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2012 until his death he presented the podcast Adam & Kompani along with [[Daniel Breitholtz]] and [[Carin da Silva]] the trio first met during filming of \"Adam Live\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/programledaren-adam-alsing-dod-i-covid-19|title=Programledaren Adam Alsing d\u00f6d i sviterna av corona|first=Lucas|last=Brischetto|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=svt.se|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415174441/https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/programledaren-adam-alsing-dod-i-covid-19|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013 and until 2017, Alsing along with [[Markoolio|Marko \"Markoolio\" Lehtosalo]] and [[Brita Zackari]] started presenting the morning show Rix MorronZoo On Rix FM.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/roger-nordin-ersatter-adam-alsing-i-radion/|title=Roger Nordin ers\u00e4tter Adam Alsing i radion|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411160357/https://www.expressen.se/noje/roger-nordin-ersatter-adam-alsing-i-radion/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAdam Alsing was the son of the former editor in chief of Aftonbladet [[Rolf Alsing]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolf Alsing, journalist|url=http://www.kau.se/alumn/alumnportratt/samhallsvetenskap-och-humaniora-5|last=Branzell|first=Karin|publisher=[[Karlstads universitet]]|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120803102341/http://www.kau.se/alumn/alumnportratt/samhallsvetenskap-och-humaniora-5|archivedate=3 August 2012|date=December 2006|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=Swedish}}</ref> He was married to his wife Anette from the early 1980s, the couple had two sons together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hant.se/noje/adam-alsing-har-varit-gift-med-anette-i-over-30-ar-det-ar-en-fantastiskt-vacker-historia/|title=Adam Alsing har varit gift med Anette i \u00f6ver 30 \u00e5r: \u201cDet \u00e4r en fantastiskt vacker historia\u201d|date=1 March 2015|website=H\u00e4nt.se|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlsing died on 15 April 2020, at the age of 51, after suffering from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/adam-alsing-dod|title=Adam Alsing d\u00f6d i covid-19|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Svenska Dagbladet}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://engnews24h.com/gry-forssell-mourns-friend-adam-alsing-taken-away-from-us/|title=Gry Forssell mourns friend Adam Alsing: \"Taken away from us\"|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Adam Alsing}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0022528}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alsing, Adam}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish radio presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "{{recent death}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adam Alsing\n| image              = Adam Alsing 2015-09-17 001.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Alsing in 2015\n| birth_name         = Rolf Adam Engelbrekt Alsing\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=y|1968|10|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|15|1968|10|12|df=yes}}\n| '''Death Cause'''  = Coronavirus (Covid-19)\n| death_place        = [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]\n| nationality        = Sweden\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Radio and television host\n| years_active       = 1990\u20132020\n| known_for          = ''[[Big Brother (Swedish TV series)|Big Brother]]'', ''[[Adam Live]]'', [[Mix Megapol]]\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n{{short description|Swedish television and radio host|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n\n'''Rolf Adam Engelbrekt Alsing''' (12 October 1968 \u2013 15 April 2020) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[television]] and radio presenter, best known for hosting ''[[Big Brother (Swedish TV series)|Big Brother Sweden]]'' on [[Kanal 5 (Swedish TV channel)|Kanal 5]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0022528/bio|title=Adam Alsing|website=IMDb|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306072844/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0022528/bio|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently he moved to [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] in 2005, hosting the Swedish version of ''[[Jeopardy!]]''. He also presented his own show ''[[Adam Live]]''. He later ventured into radio presenting shows on Rix FM and Mix Megapol.\n\n==Biography==\nAlsing grew up in [[Karlstad]] in [[V\u00e4rmland]] and [[Sollefte\u00e5]] in [[\u00c5ngermanland]]. <ref name=\"vf110902\">{{cite web|title=\u201dMan f\u00e5r s\u00e4llan en s\u00e5n h\u00e4r chans\u201d|url=https://www.vf.se/