rted presenting his own talk show called \"Adam\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> In the mid 1990s, Alsing along with Nikola S\u00f6derlund started the production company \"Think Big Productions\", they produced the shows Utmanarna on TV3, and M\u00e5ndagsklubben on [[Kanal 5 (Swedish TV channel)|Kanal 5]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gaffa.se/nyhet/142854/adam-alsing-aer-doed|title=Adam Alsing \u00e4r d\u00f6d|website=gaffa.se|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlsing presented [[Big Brother Sweden|Big Brother]] between 2000 and 2005 on Kanal 5, as well as the reality series Masterplan in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Alsing ska leda nya dokus\u00e5pan \"Masterplan\"|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/dokusapa/article10383935.ab|last=Bj\u00f6rk|first=Corinna|publisher=[[Aftonbladet]]|date=1 August 2003|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=svenska|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102131944/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/dokusapa/article10383935.ab|archive-date=2 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 2006 and 2007, he presented [[Jeopardy]] on TV4 taking over for [[Magnus H\u00e4renstam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/alsing-var-en-av-vara-stora-lattunderhallare|title=Alsing var en av v\u00e5ra stora l\u00e4ttunderh\u00e5llare|first=Andres|last=Lokko|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Svenska Dagbladet}}</ref> Between 2009 and 2011, he presented ''Sveriges v\u00e4rsta bilf\u00f6rare'' on TV4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/50g43z|title=I tv fick Adam Alsing allt f\u00f6r s\u00e4llan utlopp f\u00f6r sin stora beg\u00e5vning|website=Aftonbladet|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 5 September 2011 and 5 April 2012 Adam Alsing presented \"[[Adam Live]]\", a live talkshow on TV3, and in 2014 he presented Big Brother again this time on [[Kanal 9]].<ref>[http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/article13224970.ab Adam Alsing blir Sveriges Letterman] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820033335/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/tv/article13224970.ab |date=2017-08-20}} Aftonbladet Retrieved 15 April 2020</ref> Alsing participated as a contestant in [[P\u00e5 sp\u00e5ret]] in 2011 along with [[Stefan Holm]], the show is broadcast on [[SVT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-var-en-av-nojesvarldens-storsta/|title=Adam Alsing var en av n\u00f6jesv\u00e4rldens st\u00f6rsta|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=93&artikel=4072314|title=Holm och Alsing i \"P\u00e5 sp\u00e5ret\"|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Sveriges Radio}}</ref>\n \n=== Radio ===\nBetween 2004 and 2011, Alsing along with [[Gry Forssell]] and [[Anders Timell]] presented the radio show \u00c4ntligen morgon on Mix Megapol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-lamnar-antligen-morgon/|title=Adam Alsing l\u00e4mnar \"\u00c4ntligen morgon\"|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114211/http://www.expressen.se/noje/adam-alsing-lamnar-antligen-morgon/|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2012 until his death he presented the podcast Adam & Kompani along with [[Daniel Breitholtz]] and [[Carin da Silva]] the trio first met during filming of \"Adam Live\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/programledaren-adam-alsing-dod-i-covid-19|title=Programledaren Adam Alsing d\u00f6d i sviterna av corona|first=Lucas|last=Brischetto|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=svt.se|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415174441/https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/programledaren-adam-alsing-dod-i-covid-19|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013 and until 2017, Alsing along with [[Markoolio|Marko \"Markoolio\" Lehtosalo]] and [[Brita Zackari]] started presenting the morning show Rix MorronZoo On Rix FM.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/noje/roger-nordin-ersatter-adam-alsing-i-radion/|title=Roger Nordin ers\u00e4tter Adam Alsing i radion|website=Expressen|accessdate=15 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411160357/https://www.expressen.se/noje/roger-nordin-ersatter-adam-alsing-i-radion/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAdam Alsing was the son of the former editor in chief of Aftonbladet [[Rolf Alsing]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolf Alsing, journalist|url=http://www.kau.se/alumn/alumnportratt/samhallsvetenskap-och-humaniora-5|last=Branzell|first=Karin|publisher=[[Karlstads universitet]]|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120803102341/http://www.kau.se/alumn/alumnportratt/samhallsvetenskap-och-humaniora-5|archivedate=3 August 2012|date=December 2006|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=Swedish}}</ref> He was married to his wife Anette from the early 1980s, the couple had two sons together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hant.se/noje/adam-alsing-har-varit-gift-med-anette-i-over-30-ar-det-ar-en-fantastiskt-vacker-historia/|title=Adam Alsing har varit gift med Anette i \u00f6ver 30 \u00e5r: \u201cDet \u00e4r en fantastiskt vacker historia\u201d|date=1 March 2015|website=H\u00e4nt.se|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlsing died on 15 April 2020, at the age of 51, after suffering from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/adam-alsing-dod|title=Adam Alsing d\u00f6d i covid-19|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|via=Svenska Dagbladet}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://engnews24h.com/gry-forssell-mourns-friend-adam-alsing-taken-away-from-us/|title=Gry Forssell mourns friend Adam Alsing: \"Taken away from us\"|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Adam Alsing}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0022528}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alsing, Adam}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish radio presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden]]\n", "name_user": "BabbaQ", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Alsing"}
{"title_page": "Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name              = Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_a     = \n| native_name_r     = \n| type              =\n| seal              = \n| seal_width        = \n| seal_caption      = \n| logo              = IVV-Emblem.png\n| logo_width        = 140px\n| logo_caption      = \n| image             = KatherineJohnsonIVV.jpg\n| image_size        = 300px\n| image_caption     = The main entrance to NASA's IV&V Program.\n| formed            = 1993\n| preceding1        = \n| preceding2        = <!-- up to |preceding6= -->\n| dissolved         = \n| superseding1      = \n| superseding2      = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction      = \n| headquarters      = [[Fairmont, West Virginia]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto             = \n| employees         = 270\n| budget            = \n| minister1_name    = \n| minister1_pfo     = \n| minister2_name    = \n| minister2_pfo     = <!-- up to |minister7_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo  = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo  = <!-- up to |deputyminister7_name= -->\n| chief1_name       = Gregory Blaney\n| chief1_position   = Director\n| chief2_name       = \n| chief2_position   = <!-- up to |chief9_name= -->\n| public_protector  =\n| deputy            =\n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency     = [[NASA]], [[Goddard Space Flight Center]], [[Office of Safety and Mission Assurance]]\n| child1_agency     = \n| child2_agency     = <!-- up to |child25_agency= -->\n| keydocument1      = <!-- up to |keydocument6= -->\n| website           = {{url|nasa.gov/centers/ivv}}\n| map               = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| footnotes         = \n| embed             =\n}}\n\nNASA's '''Independent Verification & Validation (IV&V) Program''' was established in 1993 as part of an agency-wide strategy to provide the highest achievable levels of safety and cost-effectiveness for mission critical software. NASA's IV&V Program was founded under the [http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/codeq/ NASA Office of Safety and Mission Assurance (OSMA)] as a direct result of recommendations made by the National Research Council (NRC) and the Report of the Presidential Commission on the [https://history.nasa.gov/sts51l.html Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster].\n\nSince then, NASA's IV&V Program has experienced growth in personnel, projects, capabilities, and accomplishments. NASA IV&V efforts have contributed to NASA's improved safety record since the program's inception. Today, [[Independent Verification and Validation]] (IV&V) is an Agency-level function, delegated from OSMA to Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC) and managed by NASA IV&V. NASA's IV&V Program's primary business, software IV&V, is sponsored by OSMA as a software assurance technology. Having been reassigned as GSFC, NASA IV&V is Code 180 (Center Director's direct report).\n\nNASA's IV&V Program houses approximately 270 employees and leverages the expertise of in-house partners and contractors. Its facilities are located in [[Fairmont, West Virginia]]. In the summer, high school and college interns are employed in addition.\n\nOn February 22, 2019, the facility was renamed to the Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility in honor of [[Katherine Johnson]], an African-American woman who worked as a mathematician at NASA for 35 years and who is featured in the film ''[[Hidden Figures]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Gina |title=NASA Honors 'Hidden Figure' Katherine Johnson |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/the-scene/NASA-Renames-Facility-to-Honor-Hidden-Figure-Katherine-Johnson-506249461.html |website=NBC4 Washington |accessdate=25 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Affiliations ==\nNASA's IV&V Program is affiliated with [[NASA Goddard Space Flight Center]] (GSFC) and the Educator Resource Center (ERC), funded through a partnership with Fairmont State University, is part of a nationwide network of training sites at NASA centers and facilities.\n\n== Projects ==\nNASA's IV&V Program is the lead NASA organization for system software IV&V, and is responsible for the management of all system software IV&V efforts within the Agency. NASA's IV&V Program's role is to provide value-added service to the Agency's system software projects, primarily by appropriately performing IV&V on system software based on the cost, size, complexity, life span, risk, and consequences of failure.\n\n=== Independent Technical Assessments of NASA Systems ===\nNASA's IV&V Program also provides independent technical assessments of NASA systems and software processes/products to identify developmental and operational risks. This effort helps to provide assurance that safe and reliable software is being provided to NASA missions and projects as they work toward successful systems and software development. Independent assessments can address any aspect of software engineering and can be applied within any SDLC phase. This capability provides for multiple spot-checking throughout the SDLC and addresses those issues that can jeopardize mission safety and quality.\n\n=== Simulation-to-Flight 1 (STF-1) ===\nSimulation-to-Flight 1 ([[STF-1]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Simulation To Flight 1 |url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/ivv/jstar/stf1.html |website=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |publisher=NASA |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> is [[West Virginia]]\u2019s first [[CubeSat]], or small satellite. It was built under [[NASA]]\u2019s CubeSat Launch Initiative, where potential launch opportunities are provided to select CubeSat proposals from NASA Centers, accredited US educational or non-profit organizations. NASA's main goal in this initiative is to provide CubeSat developers access to a low-cost pathway to conduct research in the areas of science, exploration, technology development, education or operations. [[JSTAR]]\u2019s main goal in this mission is to fully demonstrate the capabilities of the NASA Operational Simulation (NOS) technologies, most notably its development of the NASA Operational Simulation for Small Satellites, or [http://www.stf1.com/NOS3Website/Nos3MainTab.html NOS3].\nJSTAR had a huge outreach opportunity with [[West Virginia University]] through the support of NASA IV&V and West Virginia Space Grants Consortium (WVSGC). By being partnered with JSTAR engineers and scientists, WVU Engineering, Computer Science, and Physics departments got to learn first-hand the rewards and challenges involved in working in any [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] career such as with NASA. More specifically, WVU provided their experimental ideas and worked alongside the JSTAR team to incorporate their scientific instruments into STF-1.\nAlong with offering their professional project management, JSTAR has supported WVU in their scientific development and research. By offering their software resources to this CubeSat, STF-1 has the capability of recording data once it is launched into orbit around Earth\u2014data that can be sent directly to WVU for STEM research and the education of future scientists.\nWhile community outreach is a huge component of this mission, major benefits for NASA and JSTAR have come of it as well.\n\nIn the development of these NASA Operational Simulation technologies and their demonstrations in the STF-1 mission, the IV&V tool-set has been matured to better support current and future NASA missions.\nFor example, these NOS technologies, among them NOS3, have demonstrated significant value in several areas such as: the James Webb Space Telescope, Global Precipitation Measurement, Juno, and Deep Space Climate Observatory in the areas of software development, mission operations/training, verification and validation, test procedure development, and software systems check-out.\n\nSTF-1 launched into [[Low Earth orbit]] on a [[Rocket Lab]] [[Electron]] rocket on December 16, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA Sends CubeSats to Space on First Dedicated Launch with US Partner Rocket Lab |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-sends-cubesats-to-space-on-first-dedicated-launch-with-us-partner-rocket-lab |website=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |publisher=NASA |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> As of now, STF-1 is orbiting earth in LEO and operating nominally.\n[[File:STF-1 CubeSat.jpg|thumb|none|The fully assembled STF-1 CubeSat.]]\n\n== Educator Resource Center ==\nThanks to a grant with [[Fairmont State University]], the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120612114223/http://www.nasa.gov/centers/ivv/education/erc_index.html Independent Verification and Validation Program Educator Resource Center] (ERC) provides resources and training opportunities for approximately 1,000 in-service, pre-service, and informal educators and in West Virginia annually. The materials and training cover a wide range of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) topics. The ERC also loans hands-on STEM kits to trained teachers which impact over 10,000 students per year in the state.  The on-site student outreach program brings over 2,000 youth to the facility annually to experience workshops on robotics, rocketry, aviation, and other STEM topics.  The ERC also runs numerous student STEM competitions in the fields of robotics and aviation.  Starting in 2012 the ERC became the partner for the FIRST LEGO League competition and has overseen a rapid growth in [http://WVRoboticsAlliance.org robotic competitions] that now include over 100 teams at 10 tournaments statewide each fall.\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Verification and validation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/ivv/services/ivvprojects_current.html Current projects]\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/ivv/home/index.html NASA IV&V Facility]\n*[http://www.nasa.gov/offices/education/programs/national/ercn/home/index.html NASA ERC Network]\n\n{{GSFC}}\n{{NASA centers}}\n{{NASA navbox}}\n\n{{coord|39|25|48|N|80|11|52|W|scale:10000_source:GNIS|display=title}}\n\n{{Use American English|date=January 2014}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Marion County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Goddard Space Flight Center]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:NASA facilities|Independent Verification and Validation Program]]\n[[Category:Space technology research institutes]]\n[[Category:Aerospace research institutes]]\n[[Category:Aviation research institutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n| name              = Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_a     = \n| native_name_r     = \n| type              =\n| seal              = \n| seal_width        = \n| seal_caption      = \n| logo              = IVV-Emblem.png\n| logo_width        = 140px\n| logo_caption      = \n| image             = KatherineJohnsonIVV.jpg\n| image_size        = 300px\n| image_caption     = The main entrance to NASA's IV&V Program.\n| formed            = 1993\n| preceding1        = \n| preceding2        = <!-- up to |preceding6= -->\n| dissolved         = \n| superseding1      = \n| superseding2      = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction      = \n| headquarters      = [[Fairmont, West Virginia]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto             = \n| employees         = 270\n| budget            = \n| minister1_name    = \n| minister1_pfo     = \n| minister2_name    = \n| minister2_pfo     = <!-- up to |minister7_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo  = \n| deputyminister2