{"title_page": "Envision Financial", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n|name      = Envision Financial\n|logo      = Envision Financial logo.svg\n|type      = [[Credit Union]]\n|foundation        = Delta Credit Union: 1946<br>First Heritage Savings: 1954<br>Merged as Envision Financial 2001<br>Valley First Credit Union (1947) and Envision merged as [[First West Credit Union]] (2010)\n|location_city     = [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley, British Columbia]]\n|location_country  = [[Canada]]\n|key_people        = David Lanphear, [[President (corporate title)|President]]\n|industry          = [[Financial services]]\n|homepage          = [http://www.envisionfinancial.ca envisionfinancial.ca]\n}}\n\n'''Envision Financial,''' a division of [[First West Credit Union]], is based in [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Founded in 1946, Envision Financial was established in 2001 through a merger between [[Lower Mainland]]-based Delta Credit Union, whose roots were in the fishing industry, and [[Fraser Valley]]-based First Heritage Savings Credit Union, which had historic ties to the farming and agriculture industries. First Heritage Savings Credit Union was the product of a merger between East Chilliwack Credit Union and Clearbrook District Mennonite Savings Credit Union in 1983.<ref>[https://www.envisionfinancial.ca/Personal/AboutUs/OurOrganization/OurHistory/ Our History] Envision Financial. Retrieved June 27, 2018.</ref> It is insured by the [[Credit Union Deposit Insurance Corporation of British Columbia]].\n\nIn 2008, Envision Financial entered into discussions with [[Penticton]]-based Valley First Credit Union to merge with one another and develop a new financial services organization for Western Canada. In September 2009, members at both credit unions voted in favour of the merger proposal, and on Jan. 1, 2010, Envision Financial and Valley First merged to become First West Credit Union. In 2013, Enderby & District Credit Union joined First West Credit Union, followed by Island Savings Credit Union in 2015.\n\nFirst West Credit Union has $14 billion in total assets and assets under management, approximately 1,400 employees and more than 250,000 members. The credit union is the third largest in B.C. and the fifth largest in Canada.<ref>[https://ccua.com/about-credit-unions/facts-and-figures/largest-100-credit-unions/ CCUA Facts & Figures]</ref> Its divisions\u2014Envision Financial, Valley First, Island Savings and Enderby & District Financial\u2014operate under their existing brand names in their respective markets.\n\n==About Envision Financial==\nEnvision Financial has a network of 21 branches throughout B.C. in the communities of [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], [[Chilliwack]], [[Coquitlam]], [[Delta, British Columbia|Delta]], [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]], [[Kitimat, British Columbia|Kitimat]], [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley]], [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]], [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] and [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]]. Its regional administration centre is located in Langley.\n\nFor eight consecutive years, Envision Financial was recognized as one of the 50 Best Employers in Canada by ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''{{'}}s [[Report on Business]] magazine, which publishes the annual 50 Best Employers in Canada survey conducted by [[Hewitt Associates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://was2.hewitt.com/bestemployers/canada/pages/the_list_2009.htm|title=Hewitt Associates' 50 Best Employers in Canada survey|accessdate=May 1, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608224721/http://was2.hewitt.com/bestemployers/canada/pages/the_list_2009.htm|archivedate=June 8, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2007, Envision Financial received the inaugural \"Employer of Choice\" WorkLife BC Award sponsored by the British Columbia provincial government's Ministry of Children and Family Development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marypolakmla.bc.ca/EN/mary's_local_news_2007/envision_financial_receives_worklife_bc_awards/?&PHPSESSID=46fd15946c63ac07118f90d5d27409be|title=Envision Financial Receives WorkLife BC Awards|date=February 9, 2007|accessdate=May 1, 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070930001507/http://www.marypolakmla.bc.ca/EN/mary's_local_news_2007/envision_financial_receives_worklife_bc_awards/?&PHPSESSID=46fd15946c63ac07118f90d5d27409be|archivedate=September 30, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Envision Financial is also designated a Caring Company by Imagine Canada.<ref>[http://www.imaginecanada.ca/ Imagine Canada's Caring Companies List] Retrieved June 27, 2018.</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.envisionfinancial.ca/ Envision Financial official site]\n*[[Humanomics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian banks}}\n{{Vancouver Corporations}}\n\n[[Category:First West Credit Union]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2001]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n|name      = Envision Financial\n|logo      = Envision Financial logo.svg\n|type      = [[Credit Union]]\n|foundation        = Delta Credit Union: 1946<br>First Heritage Savings: 1954<br>Merged as Envision Financial 2001<br>Valley First Credit Union (1947) and Envision merged as [[First West Credit Union]] (2010)\n|location_city     = [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley, British Columbia]]\n|location_country  = [[Canada]]\n|key_people        = David Lanphear, [[President (corporate title)|President]]\n|industry          = [[Financial services]]\n|homepage          = [http://www.envisionfinancial.ca envisionfinancial.ca]\n}}\n\n'''Envision Financial,''' a division of [[First West Credit Union]], is based in [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Founded in 1946, Envision Financial was established in 2001 through a merger between [[Lower Mainland]]-based Delta Credit Union, whose roots were in the fishing industry, and [[Fraser Valley]]-based First Heritage Savings Credit Union, which had historic ties to the farming and agriculture industries. First Heritage Savings Credit Union was the product of a merger between East Chilliwack Credit Union and Clearbrook District Mennonite Savings Credit Union in 1983.<ref>[https://www.envisionfinancial.ca/Personal/AboutUs/OurOrganization/OurHistory/ Our History] Envision Financial. Retrieved June 27, 2018.</ref> It is insured by the [[Credit Union Deposit Insurance Corporation of British Columbia]].\n\nIn 2008, Envision Financial entered into discussions with [[Penticton]]-based Valley First Credit Union to merge with one another and develop a new financial services organization for Western Canada. In September 2009, members at both credit unions voted in favour of the merger proposal, and on Jan. 1, 2010, Envision Financial and Valley First merged to become First West Credit Union. In 2013, Enderby & District Credit Union joined First West Credit Union, followed by Island Savings Credit Union in 2015.\n\nFirst West Credit Union has $14 billion in total assets and assets under management, approximately 1,400 employees and more than 250,000 members. The credit union is the third largest in B.C. and the fifth largest in Canada.<ref>https://ccua.com/about-credit-unions/facts-and-figures/largest-100-credit-unions/</ref> Its divisions\u2014Envision Financial, Valley First, Island Savings and Enderby & District Financial\u2014operate under their existing brand names in their respective markets.\n\n==About Envision Financial==\nEnvision Financial has a network of 21 branches throughout B.C. in the communities of [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], [[Chilliwack]], [[Coquitlam]], [[Delta, British Columbia|Delta]], [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]], [[Kitimat, British Columbia|Kitimat]], [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley]], [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]], [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] and [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]]. Its regional administration centre is located in Langley.\n\nFor eight consecutive years, Envision Financial was recognized as one of the 50 Best Employers in Canada by ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''{{'}}s [[Report on Business]] magazine, which publishes the annual 50 Best Employers in Canada survey conducted by [[Hewitt Associates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://was2.hewitt.com/bestemployers/canada/pages/the_list_2009.htm|title=Hewitt Associates' 50 Best Employers in Canada survey|accessdate=May 1, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608224721/http://was2.hewitt.com/bestemployers/canada/pages/the_list_2009.htm|archivedate=June 8, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2007, Envision Financial received the inaugural \"Employer of Choice\" WorkLife BC Award sponsored by the British Columbia provincial government's Ministry of Children and Family Development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marypolakmla.bc.ca/EN/mary's_local_news_2007/envision_financial_receives_worklife_bc_awards/?&PHPSESSID=46fd15946c63ac07118f90d5d27409be|title=Envision Financial Receives WorkLife BC Awards|date=February 9, 2007|accessdate=May 1, 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070930001507/http://www.marypolakmla.bc.ca/EN/mary's_local_news_2007/envision_financial_receives_worklife_bc_awards/?&PHPSESSID=46fd15946c63ac07118f90d5d27409be|archivedate=September 30, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Envision Financial is also designated a Caring Company by Imagine Canada.<ref>[http://www.imaginecanada.ca/ Imagine Canada's Caring Companies List] Retrieved June 27, 2018.</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.envisionfinancial.ca/ Envision Financial official site]\n*[[Humanomics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian banks}}\n{{Vancouver Corporations}}\n\n[[Category:First West Credit Union]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2001]]\n", "name_user": "Valueall69", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated source for footnote #2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Envision_Financial"}
{"title_page": "Tess Harper", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2007}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Tess Harper\n| image           = \n| imagesize       = \n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name       = Tessie Jean Washam\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1950|08|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Mammoth Spring, Arkansas]], U.S.\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| othername       =\n| occupation      = Actress\n| yearsactive     = 1983\u2013present\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Ken Harper|1971|1976}}\n| domesticpartner =\n| website         =\n}}\n\n'''Tessie Jean''' \"'''Tess'''\" '''Harper'''  (''n\u00e9e'' '''Washam'''; born August 15, 1950) is an American actress. She was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for her first film role in 1983's ''[[Tender Mercies]]'', and for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for the 1986 film ''[[Crimes of the Heart (film)|Crimes of the Heart]]''. Her other film appearances include ''[[Flashpoint (1984 film)|Flashpoint]]'' (1984), ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' (1987), ''[[Far North (1988 film)|Far North]]'' (1988), and ''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'' (2007). She also had a recurring role on the first three seasons of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' (2008\u20132010).\n\n==Early life==\nHarper was born on August 15, 1950, in [[Mammoth Spring, Arkansas]], the daughter of Rosemary (''n\u00e9e'' Langston) and Ed Washam. Most members of her family were quilt makers. On her own time she liked to sit on the porch swing and read. She graduated from high school in 1968. She attended [[Arkansas State University-Beebe]], where she performed in several plays, as well as Southwest Missouri State University (now [[Missouri State University]]) in [[Springfield, Missouri]], where she graduated with a degree in education.\n\n==Career==\nHarper began acting in theater productions, theme parks (including Dogpatch, USA and [[Silver Dollar City]]), [[dinner theatre]], and children's theatre. She had given up hopes of an acting career and was working for a financial institution in [[Texas]]. The institution wanted to produce a TV spot and asked her to be in the spot, which she accepted. In a twist of fate, a casting person with ''[[Tender Mercies]]'' had to spend the night in [[Dallas]] and saw Harper's spot on TV. She called [[Robert Duvall]] and arranged an audition. Director [[Bruce Beresford]] was impressed with Harper and cast her in the lead female role of Rosa Lee, the young widow and mother who marries [[country music|country singer]] Mac Sledge. Beresford said that Harper brought a kind of rural quality to the role without coming across as simple or foolish. He said of Harper, \"She walked into the room and even before she spoke, I thought, 'That's the girl to play the lead.'\"<ref name=\"Miracles\">{{cite video |people= [[Bruce Beresford]] (actor), [[Robert Duvall]] (actor), Tess Harper (actor), Gary Hertz (director) |date= April 16, 2002 |title= Miracles & Mercies |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0383509/ |medium= Documentary |publisher= [[Blue Underground]] |location= [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]], [[California]] |accessdate= January 28, 2008}}</ref> Harper did not realize this, and recalled shortly after the film's release, \"After I did the final [[screen test]], I went to see ''[[Breaker Morant (film)|Breaker Morant]]'' and started sobbing uncontrollably halfway through it. A friend had to take me home, and I kept crying, 'You don't understand! They're not gonna let me do this part!'\"<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first=  |title=Success, Stress and Tess Harper|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 9, 1983 |issue=397|page=40}}</ref>\n\n''Tender Mercies'' was Harper's feature film debut. She later said that she was so excited about the role that she bit her script just to make sure it was real, and she was so nervous that during her first take she feared the filmmakers would \"come to their senses and say, 'We're sorry, we made a terrible mistake.'\"<ref name=\"Miracles\" /> Duvall, who played the lead role of Mac Sledge, did his best to help Harper in her first film role. During one scene in which Mac Sledge and Rosa Lee were fighting, Duvall yelled at a [[make-up artist]] in front of Harper specifically to make her angry for the scene; Duvall apologized to the make-up artist after the scene was shot. After filming, Duvall said Harper did a very good job, and he felt her rural past in Arkansas helped her in the part.<ref name=\"Miracles\" /> She earned a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for the role. Duvall won the [[Academy Award]] for Best Actor for his performance.\n\nHarper appeared in the TV mini-series [[Chiefs (miniseries)|''Chiefs'']] (1983) and ''[[Celebrity (television series)|Celebrity]]'' (1984), as well as many [[television movie]]s including ''[[Starflight: The Plane That Couldn't Land]]'' (1983) and ''Reckless Disregard'' (1985). In 1983, she appeared in the full-length feature ''[[Silkwood]]''. In 1986, Harper was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for her work as Chick Boyle in ''[[Crimes of the Heart (film)|Crimes of the Heart]]'', which was directed by her ''Tender Mercies'' director Bruce Beresford. She later played parts in ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' (1987), ''Far North'' (1988), ''[[The Man in the Moon]]'' (1991), ''[[The Jackal (1997 film)|The Jackal]]'' (1997) and ''[[Loggerheads (2005 film)|Loggerheads]]'' (2005). She also took part in [[Michael Jackson|Michael Jackson's]] [[Black Or White]] (1991) musical minifilm.\n\nHarper had a regular role on the [[CBS]] series ''[[Christy (TV series)|Christy]]'', from 1994-95. Her roles have frequently been that of a Southern lady, although she had worked to lose her [[Arkansas]] accent. She also had a recurring role on another [[CBS]] [[Television program|television series]], ''[[Early Edition]]'', from 1996 to 2000. She portrayed the mother of lead character Gary Hobsen. Harper shared a [[Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Award]] (in the Best Ensemble Cast category) with her fellow cast members in the Oscar-winning film ''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'', in which she played the wife of [[Tommy Lee Jones|Tommy Lee Jones's]] character.\n\nShe had the recurring role of Mrs. Pinkman on ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', appearing in the first three seasons.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Tender Mercies]]''\n|Rosa Lee\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Amityville 3-D]]''\n|Nancy Baxter\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Silkwood]]''\n|Linda Dawson\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Flashpoint (1984 film)|Flashpoint]]''\n|Ellen\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Crimes of the Heart (film)|Crimes of the Heart]]''\n|Chick Boyle\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]''\n|Willa\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Far North (1988 film)|Far North]]''\n|Rita\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Criminal Law (film)|Criminal Law]]''\n|Det. Stillwell\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Her Alibi]]''\n|Sally Blackwood\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Daddy's Dyin': Who's Got the Will?]]''\n|Sara Lee Turnover\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[My Heroes Have Always Been Cowboys (film)|My Heroes Have Always Been Cowboys]]''\n|Cheryl\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''{{sortname|The|Man in the Moon}}''\n|Abigail Trant\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''Pretty Hattie's Baby''\n|Maya\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''{{sortname|The|Turning|The Turning (1992 film)}}''\n|Martha Harnish\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[My New Gun]]''\n|Kimmy Hayes\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''Dirty Laundry''\n|Beth Greene\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[The Jackal (1997 film)|The Jackal]]''\n|The First Lady\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''{{sortname|The|In Crowd|The In Crowd (2000 film)}}''\n|Dr. Amanda Giles\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''{{sortname|The|Rising Place|nolink=1}}''\n|Rebecca Hodge\n